<HEADLINE> Visiting Philippine President Meets Greek Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Philippine President Fidel
Ramos held talks today with his Greek counterpart, Costis
Stephanopoulos and Prime Minister Costas Simitis on bilateral
ties, the situation in the Balkans, Southeast Europe and
Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
During his visit here, the first by a Philippine head of
state, President Ramos will sign a number of agreements and
memoranda of understanding on culture, tourism, investments and
economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Stephanopoulos said relations between the two countries were
good and prospects for furthering bilateral cooperation were
bright.
</P>
<P>
The substantial presence of Filipinos in Greece constituted an
additional bond in bilateral relations, he added.
</P>
<P>
Ramos, who arrived here Sunday for a three-day official visit,
said relations between the two countries were strengthened through
dialogue between the European Union (EU) and the Association
of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN).
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need to expand bilateral cooperation in the
fields of commerce, shipbuilding and investment.
</P>
<P>
Discussions for an agreement on protecting investments in each
other's countries would start soon, he added.
</P>
<P>
Greece is the last leg of Ramos' current three-nation trip,
which has already taken him to Britain and Oman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
