<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Chief Spells out Upcoming Agenda in Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, June 23 (Xinhua) -- NATO Secretary General Javier
Solana on Monday spelled out a mild four-item task in the coming
months for the NATO-led Stabilization Force (SFOR) in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference here that "there are still major
obstacles in the implementation of the Dayton peace agreement",
although the military provisions have been well carried out.
</P>
<P>
"We have many challenges to face in the months ahead," Solana
said, adding that four of them are the most urgent.
</P>
<P>
The challenges are to remove illegal local police checkpoints,
open more airports to civil air traffic, put into function the
standing military committee to foster confidence among the Bosnian
parties and provide secure environment for upcoming municipal
elections.
</P>
<P>
Besides Sarajevo airport, NATO peace-keeping forces are ready
to turn over those in Banja Luka, Tuzla and Mostar for civilian
use, Solana said.
</P>
<P>
But the initiative was still blocked by local politicians
concerned with "little politics than the benefits of opening those
airports", he said.
</P>
<P>
Solana reiterated his demand that Bosnian leaders do more in
ensuring a lasting peace in the country in the following 12 months
before the expiration of the current mandate of the NATO
peace-keeping mission.
</P>
<P>
"These months will pass quickly. The leaders of Bosnia must use
this time efficiently and productively to lay the basis for
enduring peace. I don't think they will have a better opportunity
than the one in front of them now," he said.
</P>
<P>
Solana was on a one-day visit to Sarajeva, during which he met
with leaders of the Bosnian parties and the international
community's new High Representative Carlos Westendorp, who is also
a former Spanish foreign minister like Solana himself. 
</P>
</TEXT>
