<HEADLINE> Australia Beat Argentina in World Youth Soccer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Kostas Salapasidis scored
four goals, including a last-minute penalty to help Australia
beat defending champions Argentina 4-3 in the world youth soccer
championships on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The victory lifted Australia to the top of group E and left
second-placed Argentina the daunting prospect of tackling England
and then Brazil for a place in the semi-finals.
</P>
<P>
England won group F with a 1-0 win over Mexico, who finished
second and faced a tough pre-quarter-final against France at
Kuching on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Young Liverpool star Michael Owens scored the match-winner in
the 65th minute to maintain England's all-win record in group F at
Johor Baru.
</P>
<P>
England play Argentina next on Thursday with the winner almost
certain to face favorites Brazil in the quarter-finals. Brazil
are due to play Belgium, a third-placed qualifier, in their next
match.
</P>
<P>
Japan fought out a thrilling 3-3 draw with Paraguay on Monday
to finish second behind Spain in group D. Japan face Australia at
Kangar on Thursday for a place in the quarter-finals.
</P>
<P>
Spain routed lowly Costa Rica 4-0 to win all their three league
matches and emerge as one of the strongest contenders for the
under-20 crown.
</P>
<P>
Canada joined Argentina and Australia in the knock-out rounds
from group E with a 2-1 victory over Hungary, who lost all their
three matches in the under-20 tournament.
</P>
<P>
Another surprise on an eventful night was the United Arab
Emirates making it to the knock-out rounds with a 2-0 win over
Ivory Coast.
</P>
<P>
The UAE, who had lost their previous two matches by identical
0-5 margins, qualified as one of the four third-placed teams and
now face Group C champions Ghana in the next round. 
</P>
</TEXT>
