<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Electornic Scoring in Mediterranean Games Overturned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 23 (Xinhua) -- An Italian heavyweight boxer was
stripped of a gold medal earned in the Mediterranean Games after a
committee ruled that electornic scoring was wrong.
</P>
<P>
It was believed to be the first time that the high-tech
computerised scoring way applied at Olympics and world
championships had been overruled.
</P>
<P>
The ruling came despite the earlier insistence of world amateur
boxing body AIBA that the verdict was good.
</P>
<P>
Italian Giacobbe Fragomeni won the gold last Thursday when he
outpointed Algerian Mohammed Benguesmia 3-2 on points.
</P>
<P>
Algeria made a formal complaint when it emerged that four of
the five judges had Benguesmia ahead on their back-up scorecards.
</P>
<P>
The International Committee of the Mediterranean Games declared
after a hearing that Algeria's protest was upheld and Benguesmia
should be awarded the gold. Fragomeni was given the silver medal.
</P>
</TEXT>
