<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CIS Becomes Cyprus' Main Tourist Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Russia and other former Soviet
Republics have become the most expanding tourist market for
Cyprus since the number of tourists from this area is increasing
rapidly.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released here today by the Association of Cyprus
Travel Agency (ACTA) show that in 1996, about 130,000 tourists
came to Cyprus from the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS),
representing 6.7 percent of the year's total number of tourists,
while in 1993, only 21,000 tourists visited Cyprus from that
region.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.K. is still the dominant tourist market for
Cyprus with 720,000 visitors in 1996, representing 36.9 percent
of the total, followed by Germany with 240,000 (12.3 percent),
the Scandinavian countries with 235,000 (12.0 percent) and Russia.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, visitors to the island spent an average 382
Cyprus pounds (about 764 U.S. dollars) per visitor, compared
with 389.6 pounds (about 779.2 U.S. dollars) spent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
According to an earlier announcement, in 1996, a total of
1,950,000 foreign tourist visited this Eastern Mediterranean
island, showing a slight drop from the previous year of 2.1
million tourist arrivals.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus launched a publicity campaign abroad this year to
challenge the competitiveness from other tourist destinations.
</P>
<P>
The tourist sector, on which the island's economy heavily
relys, earned about 1.6 billion U.S. dollars every year,
representing about 40 percent of the total revenue from the
export of goods and services together. 
</P>
</TEXT>
