<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Pak, India Agree to Agenda for Future Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 23 (Xinhua) -- There has been a significant
forward movement in the second round of Pak-India foreign
secretary-level talks as the two countries agreed to an agenda,
including the long-running issue of Jammu and Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
The two South Asian nations have also agreed to the
establishment of a mechanism, including joint working groups for
conduct of future talks on all outstanding issues.
</P>
<P>
This is the major achievement of the three-day talks which
ended here earlier today between the foreign secretaries of
Pakistan and India.
</P>
<P>
A joint statement released today at the end of three-day
intensive discussions said that "with the objective of promoting a
friendly and harmonious relationship between Pakistan and India,
the two countries have agreed to address all outstanding issues of
concern to both sides."
</P>
<P>
These issues include peace and security, Jammu and Kashmir,
Siachen, terrorism and drug-trafficking, economic and commercial
cooperation and promotion of friendly exchanges in various fields.
</P>
<P>
As a major breakthrough in the bilateral talks, Pakistan and
India also agreed to setting up a mechanism, including working
groups at appropriate levels, to address all these issues in an
integrated manner.
</P>
<P>
According to the joint statement, the core issues of peace and
security and Jammu and Kashmir will be dealt with at the level of
foreign secretaries who will also coordinate and monitor the work
of all the working groups.
</P>
<P>
During the second round of talks, Pakistan's Foreign Secretary
Shamshad Ahmed and his Indian counterpart Salman Haider also had a
preliminary exchange of views on the composition of the working
groups and their methodology.
</P>
<P>
It is decided that the two countries will continue the
consideration of this matter through diplomatic channels, and the
next round of foreign secretary-level talks will be held in the
Indian capital of New Delhi in September this year.
</P>
<P>
As a good-will gesture, the two countries will release fishing
boats and their crew presently in the custody of either side and
take all possible steps to prevent hostile propaganda and
provocative actions against each other.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint news conference held here at the end of the
talks, Shamshad Ahmed said that "Pakistan and India have
successfully completed the first stage of the task on identifying
the outstanding issues between the two countries and on devising a
mechanism to address them purposefully."
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the mechanism on which we have agreed will
initiate progress towards the settlement of all outstanding
issues," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani foreign secretary stressed that his country will
continue the dialogue "with sincerity and serious purpose."
</P>
<P>
Shamshad Ahmed, however, said that "we have no illusions about
the complexity of the work ahead of us." "It is important for both
sides now to take steps to create conditions conducive towards the
process purposeful and resultful."
</P>
<P>
Salman Haider, who led a six-member Indian delegation in the
talks, said on the occasion that the joint statement issued at the
end of the talks provided "the basis for comprehensive,
constructive and sustained dialogue between India and Pakistan."
</P>
<P>
While commenting the latest round of bilateral talks, Pakistani
Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan said, "it is a very progressive
step."
</P>
<P>
"Our satisfaction is that for the first time that the Jammu and
Kashmir issue has been put on the agenda for working groups along
with other issues," the foreign minister said, adding that the
talks were "positive, progressive and constructive."
</P>
<P>
The latest round of foreign secretary-level talks was held as
agreed upon by the prime ministers of Pakistan and India at their
meeting during the Summit of the South Asian Association for
Regional Cooperation in Male last month.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan and India resumed their foreign secretary-level talks
in New Delhi late March after a suspension of more than three
years due to the increased tension.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
