<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Janata Party Chief Charged in Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 23 (Xinhua) -- India's Central Bureau of
Investigation (CBI) today filed a charge sheet against Janata
Party President and Bihar State chief minister, Laloo Prasad
Yadav, and 50 others for their alleged involvement in a
multi-crore rupee fodder scandal, Press Trust of India said.
</P>
<P>
The 50-page charge sheet, along with 1,000 pages of annexes,
was filed in the designated court of Justice S.K. Lal here this
evening.
</P>
<P>
In the scandal which involved 9.5 billion rupees (about 270
million U.S. dollars), 56 people, including Yadav, was accused of
looting the Bihar state treasury through embezzling public funds
sanctioned for fodder supplies in the state.
</P>
<P>
Though the alleged fraudulent withdrawals from the state
treasury started in 1985, the scandal did not erupt until January
last year.
</P>
<P>
As the investigations into the case went on, huge pressures
have been amounted upon Yadav in the past few months for him to
resign.
</P>
<P>
Yadav has refused to quit saying that the case was a conspiracy
masterminded by the opposition Bharatiya Janata Party and the CBI
to dislodge him and his government in Bihar, the second most
populous state in India.
</P>
<P>
The other accused included one former Bihar chief minister and
several former central government ministers.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters soon after the CBI filed the charge sheet
against him today, Yadav reiterated his unwillingness to quit
office.
</P>
<P>
"I will not resign unless my guilt is proved in the court," he
said, adding that mere submission of charge sheet does not prove
anybody guilty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
