<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Workshop on Disaster Vulnerability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 23 (Xinhua) -- An international workshop
entitled ''Vulnerability in Ethiopia'' was opened here today with a
view to devising a mechanism to eliminate the root causes of
vulnerabilities to man-made and natural disasters in the country.
</P>
<P>
The three-day workshop, organized by the Ethiopia's Disaster
Prevention and Preparedness Commission, is attended by representatives
from the Ethiopian government, regional administrations, foreign
embassies, the United Nations agencies and donor organizations.
</P>
<P>
In his opening speech, Simon Mechale, Commisioner for the Disaster
Prevention and Preparedness Commission, said ''problems associated
with vulnerability can best be solved through engagement in long-
term development for which the right policies, plans and implemen-
tation arrangements are already in place.''
</P>
<P>
He said ''disaster prevention programs shall be given due
emphasis in all spheres of development endeavours and that all
relief programs shall be geared towards eliminating the root
cause of vulnerability to disaster''.
</P>
<P>
He described the workshop as a forum for discussing the best
ways and means of identifying the key problems associated with the
country's vulnerability to disasters and charting out the appropriate
course of action.
</P>
<P>
The workshop has objectives to identifying instruments for
integrating development efforts in disaster prone areas with
disaster prevention and converging efforts in order to tackle the
problem through cooperation and the creation of focal points and
networks. It will also provide survey of areas most vulnerable to
disaster in recent history and those likely to be in the future.
enditem

