<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-23 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Opposes U.S. Decision on Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul
Salam al Majali said here today that his country supports efforts
by Arab countries to stop the implementation of a U.S. Congress'
vote on recognizing Jerusalem as Israel's unified capital.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark at a press conference before his departure
for Bahrain after a three-day official visit to the United Arab
Emirates (UAE).
</P>
<P>
The U.S. House of Representative vote was passed on June 10 and
set aside 100 million dollars to move the U.S. Embassy from Tel
Aviv to Jerusalem, a city also claimed by Palestinians as the
capital of their future state.
</P>
<P>
Majali stressed that his country always insists on Israel's
withdrawal from occupied Arab lands and that Jerusalem is Arab
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Majali discussed with UAE senior officials
the latest developments in the Middle East region and bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
Referring to a recently-singed Israeli-Turkish military
cooperation pact, Majali said that Jordan will be against the pact
if it aims at Syria or Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"A military coalition brings no settlements (to conflicts) in a
period of peace because the world has rejected such ways," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that his country is concerned by the stalled
Middle East peace process, urging Israel to commit itself to UN
resolutions and agreements signed with Arabs on the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East peace talks have been deadlocked since March
when Israel started the construction of Jewish settlement in East
Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
