<HEADLINE> East Africa Starts Insurance Plan to Attract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 23 (Xinhua) -- A newly-launched insurance scheme
seeks to increase confidence amongst foreign tourists to eastern
Africa by offering medical care or evacuation in case of
accidents or serious illness.
</P>
<P>
For 30 U.S. Dollars for each holiday-maker per month, tour
firms can ensure that their clients have insurance cover valid
throughout eastern Africa and the Seychelles Islands.
</P>
<P>
A related medical insurance cover is one offered by the Kenya
Flying Doctors Service at 25 Dollars within a 500-kilometer
radius of Nairobi, covering the whole of Kenya and parts of
northern Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Those seeking cover beyond that limit pay 50 Dollars for a
flying doctor service that goes as far as Ethiopia and the Indian
Ocean island nation of Mauritus.
</P>
<P>
"Through this scheme, the 30-Dollar offers insurance cover of
up to one million Dollars in the event of accident or other
emergency-related eventualities," Job Kareithi, a former Kenya
Air Force captain who designed the scheme, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Tourism has become increasingly sensitive due to issues of
safety and some of the cost cannot be met by individual tour
operators," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The scheme is sold directly to individuals or through tour
firms.
</P>
<P>
An official of the Flying Doctors Service said they handle an
average of four to five evacuations every week, mainly malaria or
diarrhoea cases, in the region.
</P>
<P>
During the tourist-peak season, the number of evacuations are
higher, he said. enditem

=06231635

