<HEADLINE> Inclusion of Kashmir in Pak-India Talks, Major </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif has termed the inclusion of the Kashmir issue on agenda of
Pak-India talks a major "breakthrough".
</P>
<P>
Talking to the local media here today, Sharif said that the
long standing disputes between India and Pakistan will be resolved
through negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"It has raised the hope to solve the core issues between the
two countries," Sharif added.
</P>
<P>
"Our sincerity yielded the success which could not be achieved
during the last fifty years," the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Pakistan's Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan also said
the inclusion of the Kashmir issue on the agenda for future talks
between Pakistan and India is a major breakthrough and it has been
brought on the agenda for the first time in the history of
Pakistan and India.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan and India ended here today their three-day talks
between the foreign secretaries of the two countries. A joint
statement issued at the end of the talks said that the two
countries agreed to an agenda for future talks on all outstanding
issues including the Kashmir issue.  
</P>
</TEXT>
