<HEADLINE> PNA Officials: More Violence Possible Over Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Senior Palestinian officials
today renewed warnings to Israel about the possibility of a new
wave of Palestinian violence if the current impasse in the peace
talks continues.
</P>
<P>
Minister for Jerusalem Affairs of the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) Faisal Husseini told reporters in Gaza that the
continued Israeli settlement activities could trigger a new wave
of Palestinian violence.
</P>
<P>
He demanded Israel fulfill its commitments to the signed
agreements with the Palestinian side.
</P>
<P>
Husseini also attacked the United States Congress for its
recognition of Israel's claim to the whole Jerusalem as its
eternal capital and for its decision to move the U.S. embassy from
Tel Aviv to the holy city.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, PNA Culture and Information Minister Yasser Abed
Rabbo warned Israel that the Palestinian people were ready for
war in which they would defend their land to death.
</P>
<P>
The warnings followed the recent confrontations in the
Gaza Strip and the West Bank city Hebron, where stone-throwing
Palestinian protesters had clashed with Israeli soldiers for
several days in mid-June.
</P>
<P>
A day earlier, PNA President Yasser Arafat also expressed deep
concern over the peace deadlock caused by the hardline policies
of the Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to visiting members from Israel's leftist Hadash
Party in Ramallah, Arafat said Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu did not realize the seriousness of his actions and the
possible consequences in the regional context, as well as in the
terms of Israeli-Palestinian relations.
</P>
<P>
Today, Arafat met in Ramallah with Assad Assad, Netanyahu's
adviser on Israeli Druse affairs, who reportedly conveyed a
message from the Israeli premier to the PNA leader on the
current situation.
</P>
<P>
Assad said that Arafat asked him to bring back a message to
Netanyahu after the meeting, but he did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
He quoted Arafat as saying that Israel and the PNA should
resolve their differences in direct dialogs, including a meeting
between himself and Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Egyptian peace envoy Osama el-Baz is expected, by
the end of this week, to renew his efforts for the resumption of
the Israeli-Palestinian talks, which have been frozen since
March when the Israeli government gave the order to begin
building the Har Homa settlement in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Baz's previous shuttle missions have failed to break the
deadlock between the two sides. The PNA demands Israel stop all
settlement activities before resuming the talks, while Israel
insists that the PNA should resume security cooperation with
Israel and sit down to talk without preconditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
