<HEADLINE> Photo Exhibition on Hong Kong's Return to China Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 23 (Xinhua) -- A photographic exhibition on the
history and development of Hong Kong opened here tonight to mark
the historic occasion of Hong Kong's return to China, which will
take place on July 1.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition features more than 200 photographs and is
divided into four broad categories -- "History of Hong Kong," "The
Link between Hong Kong and the Inland of China," "The Course of
Hong Kong's Return," and "Hong Kong Today."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony, George Yeo, Minister for
Information and the Arts and Second Minister for Trade and
Industry of Singapore, said the return of Hong Kong on July 1,
1997 to China is an historic event. "It marks the final closing of
a difficult chapter of history for East Asians."
</P>
<P>
The key reason for the loss of Hong Kong to the British was not
British might but Chinese weakness, the minister observed, adding
that in the same way, the return of Hong Kong to China on July 1
this year reflects the resurgence of Asia and its ability now to
deal with Western powers on the basis of equality.
</P>
<P>
"If China were still backward and mired in civil war, the
coming return of Hong Kong to China would probably not take
place," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We in Singapore are not only observers of the important event
that is to take place on July 1, we are also participants in it
because of our stake in the promotion of peace and prosperity in
Asia and the world," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he said, "This exhibition of the history and
development of Hong Kong not only reminds us of the past, it also
points our way into the future."
</P>
<P>
Fu Xuezhang, Chinese ambassador to Singapore, said he is
confident that after its return, Hong Kong's links with Singapore
will grow closer and the economic cooperation between the two will
be more fruitful.
</P>
<P>
"Under the new circumstances, Hong Kong and Singapore will grow
and prosper together," he said, noting that the Singapore
government had expressed its full confidence in Hong Kong's future
and its commitment to continued investment in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
He also reiterated that after its return, Hong Kong will retain
its existing social and economic systems, legal framework and way
of life. It will enjoy a high degree of autonomy, he said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's status as a trade, transportation and financial
center in the region will not be affected. Rather, it will be
consolidated and grow further, the ambassador stressed.
</P>
<P>
"Facts will prove that 'one country, two systems' will be the
optimal formula for China's great cause of national
reunification," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
