<HEADLINE> Feature: Somalis Make Money by Exporting Junk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Somali businessmen are making
money by exporting junk lying in the streets of the war-divided
capital, Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
As debris of different kind lies in heaps in the main streets
of Mogadishu due to poor sanitation, the idea of exporting some
of them is also some relief for the people.
</P>
<P>
The item which is being added to the few exportable items of
Somalia is animal bones. There are mountains of bones of camel,
goats and cattle in Mogadishu, of which the largest, 13 meters
high and about 50 meters wide, lies in North Mogadishu while the
second largest is in South Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
According to Mohamud Cattivo, the owner of one of the two bone
grinding plants in Mogadishu, their business is booming with a
lot of revenue being made.
</P>
<P>
He said they grind the bones in three different sizes: gravel
size, millet size and powdering, adding that "those are the
required sizes for exporting the stuff to the United Arab
Emirates."
</P>
<P>
"We would get the bones free of charge just a month ago, but
now the people came to know that they're worthy while," he said,
"and we're obliged to buy from them in kilograms."
</P>
<P>
The bones are sold in two categories, some containing its bone
marrows and others dried up. According to Cattivo, the bones
containing its marrow are two times more expensive than the
others since the fats are extracted and resold again for the
local consumption.
</P>
<P>
Each quintal of the dry bones are bought from local collectors
about one US Dollar and the same quintal can be sold in the UAE
about 100-120 US Dollars after the process and shipment, said
Cattivo. He added that they also export dried blood and animal
waste which they grind together as food for cattle and chicken.
</P>
<P>
The process of the bones collection is also creating numerable
jobs for many of the poor Somalis. Over 200 people are currently
busy in collecting animal bones from the streets of Mogadishu and
its surrounding districts every day.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, 51 people permanently work in the South Mogadishu
Bone Grinding Machinery, who so far ground 100 tons of bones in
less than 20 days. Abdulle Awleh, the owner of the North
Mogadishu Bone Processing Plant said his factory employs more
than 100 people permanently.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the hard currency injection to the already dead
economy of the country, this business is on the other hand taking
part in the improvement of the sanitation and hygiene in the
capital.
</P>
<P>
Other businessmen are also planning to get a market for the
other residues such as the peels of the fruit, worn-out shoes,
the plastic bags for export. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
