<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Earth Summit+5 Opens at UN Headquarters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The 19th special session of
the General Assembly of the United Nations, also known as Earth
Summit+5, opened here today.
</P>
<P>
The week-long session aims to review action taken in the five
years since the United Nations Conference on Environment and
Development met in Rio de Janeiro and to set priorities into the
21st century.
</P>
<P>
At the opening session, President of the General Assembly and
Malaysia Ambassador Razali Ismail said reviewing the
implementation of the Agenda 21 must go beyond simply calculation
ratios of progress versus deterioration. This was a time for
critical reflection and concrete action.
</P>
<P>
Razali said there had been notable achievements since Rio.
Prime among them had been the unfolding of Agenda 21 into a living
document beyond the realm of conferences. National strategies,
local initiatives, public consciousness and environment had
proliferated, accompanied by tentative reforms of institutions and
aid programs. On the global level population growth rate had
stabilized, infant mortality fallen, life expectancy increased and
nutrition improved.
</P>
<P>
The elaboration of the Rio Declaration into legal principles
and international law was also a notable achievement. But the end
result remained paltry, due to the slowness in dealing with
issues, the inconsistent fulfillment of agreements, and the weak
ability to enforce compliance and to ensure the equitable benefits
for all, the president said.
</P>
<P>
He said five years on from Rio, the international community
still faced a recession of the very political will that was
essential for realizing real change. Failure in the management of
natural resources continued to create scarcities, to invite
conflicts, to pose dangers to public health and to incite social
disintegration. Those at Rio who made serious commitments had not
followed through on their promises.
</P>
<P>
Challenging governments North and South to tackle the real
obstacles to implement the Agenda 21, he stressed it is necessary
to avoid the temptation to concentrate on just so-called emerging
issues. The crucial issues were the cross-sectoral issues, those
that linked environment and development.
</P>
<P>
"Governments and NGOs from the developed world vigorously
promote environmental protection, without shouldering the greater
burden of adjustment of consumption and production patterns. Nor do
they emphasize with equal balance the importance of fulfilling
global responsibilities with national ones," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Levels of development assistance are not even graced with the
tag of 'business as usual'. Official development assistance has
sharply declined from 55 billion dollars to less than 50 billion
dollars since Rio. There no signs the decline will be reversed and
this remains a blow to international cooperation," he added.
</P>
<P>
He urged governments, private sector and members of civil
society to address new challenges so as to fulfill the global
commitments and realize sustainable development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
