<HEADLINE> Israeli Flower Growers Seek International </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Banks from France and Holland
are competing with the Bank of Israel over the financing of the
Israeli flower industry projects valued at 19 million
U.S. dollars, according to a report of bi-weekly Israel Business
Today.
</P>
<P>
A statement to this effect was issued by the Horticulturalist
Council earlier this month following government approval of
guarantees for flower growers.
</P>
<P>
The council said that it is conducting negotiations with a
number of international banks with regard to the financing of
flower-growing projects. The financing in question would be
provided in the form of loans granted to the agriculturalists as
complementary funding to equity and a grant given by the
Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, agriculturalists have experienced
difficulties in returning bank loans and this has generated
delays in investment in flower-growing projects due to lack of
funds.
</P>
<P>
A number of banks from Israel and abroad have applied to the
Horticulturalist Council with a request to participate in the
credit program. The Council's comptroller, Micha Kenig, flew to
Europe earlier this month to hold talks with senior managers at
the Commercial-Industrial Bank of France and the Dutch
International Bank to discuss the terms and level of financing.
</P>
<P>
Israel is a major flower-exporting country, only after Holland
and Columbia. However, flower growers recently went on strike
against the lack of government support for the industry, which,
according to them, caused the decline in flower exports to
Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
