<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief Calls for Global Partnership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 23 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan today called for global efforts for sustainable development
at the Special Session of the General Assembly on review of the
implementation of Agenda 21.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening session, Annan said our task in this
session was to turn that political will into deeds and actions. We
must set a sure course for the world community into the new
millennium, on this most urgent and vital global issue.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the United Nations Conference on Environment and
Development (UNCED) in 1992 was a landmark in the new global
diplomacy. It brought together governments, non-government
organizations and concerned individuals as never before. Its
objectives, scope and focus were loftier than any previous
conference, its basis of support broader, and its implementing
partners more varied.
</P>
<P>
Annan said UNCED marked a conceptual breakthrough, too. It gave
practical effect to the relationship between environment and
development in the new concept of "sustainable development", which
embraced the human and social dimension of sustainable
development. It generated new hope that poverty and deprivation
could be attacked with greater clarity and coherence.
</P>
<P>
On progress achieved in the last five years, he said many
countries established national coordinating mechanisms for
sustainable development and implementation of Agenda 21, all three
conventions on climate change, biodiversity and combating
desertification entered into force, and notable progress was made
in switching to renewable energy sources.
</P>
<P>
On the negative side, he noted that more than a quarter of the
developing world's people still lived in absolute poverty, no
progress had been made in following up UNCED commitments for the
transfer of concessional finance and environmentally sound
technology to developing countries, carbon dioxide emissions
continued to rise, one third of the world's population lived in
countries facing moderate to severe stress on water resources and
majority of species subject to fishing in oceans were now fully
exploited or over-exploited.
</P>
<P>
He called on the governments and the United Nations to join
with the private sector, civil society and non-government
organizations in a new partnership based on a recognition of
mutual interests and a readiness to share responsibilities,
which would link all global environment stake-holders in an
alliance to implement the Agency 21. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
