<HEADLINE> Cypriot President to Go to New York for Direct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides will go to New York next month, accompanied by
parliamentary party leaders, for direct negotiations with Turkish
Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash, it was announced here today.
</P>
<P>
"President Clerides is going to New York and the presence of
the party leaders will facilitate the assessment of developments
at any given moment," government spokesman Manolis Christofides
said in statements following a four-hour meeting of the National
Council, which comprises five parliamentary party leaders.
</P>
<P>
The Council, the top advisory body to the president, met
today in a bid to forge a strategy which Clerides will follow in
the U.N.-sponsored direct negotiations with Denktash in New York
from July 9 to 13.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that Clerides was satisfied with today's
meeting, during which no disagreements surfaced and party leaders
suggested ways on how the negotiations will succeed.
</P>
<P>
"They have responsibly expressed views and made suggestions
on how these negotiations could succeed," Christofides said.
</P>
<P>
The government spokesman said that there was understanding on
issues faced by the Greek Cypriot side and that "the picture
presented today is very encouraging."
</P>
<P>
He also noted that party leaders going to New York are, for
the time being, accompanying the president to the first round of
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said in a recent report to
the U.N. Security Council on his good offices mission in Cyprus
that a second round of direct negotiations will be held in
August and a third one may be held if deemed necessary.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also expressed the hope that Turkey will
demonstrate flexibility during the talks.
</P>
<P>
"Turkey's stance concerns us because it presents a picture of
intransigence. But we look forward to these negotiations and we
expect there will be some flexibility if the goal is to find a
solution to the Cyprus problem. That is our goal," Christofides
said.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unresolved since 1974 when
the island was divided after the Turkish troops occupied its
northern third in the wake of a pro-Athens coup.
</P>
</TEXT>
