<HEADLINE> British Court Jails Kray 12 Years for Drug Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The British court today sentenced
Charlie Kray, the elder brother of former British gangland twins
Reggie and Ronnie Kray, for 12-year imprisonment for masterminding
a 39 million pound (65 million US dollars) cocaine plot.
</P>
<P>
But the 70-year-old Kray protested his innocence, saying that
during his whole life he had "advised people never to be involved
in drugs."
</P>
<P>
However the jury, which on Friday convicted Kray of supplying
and offering to supply cocaine, was clearly of the opinion that he
had failed to follow his own advice.
</P>
<P>
Kray was convicted of offering to supply two undercover police
officers with five kg (11 lb) of cocaine every fortnight for two
years. He was also found guilty of actually supplying two kg (4.4
lb).
</P>
<P>
Kray's friends and relatives have said he will appeal against
his conviction.
</P>
<P>
His brothers Reggie and Ronnie, London's most prominent gang
bosses during the 1960s, were jailed for life in 1969 for the
murders of fellow criminals George Cornell and Jack "The Hat"
McVitie.
</P>
<P>
Ronnie died of a heart attack last year in Broadmoor
psychiatric hospital, home to many of Britain's most disturbed
criminals. Reggie, 62, remains in prison. 
</P>
</TEXT>
