<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-23 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Beit El-Mal Holdings, an Islamic financial
institution based in Ramallah, the West Bank, has started the
construction of a large commercial center in Nablus as part of
its commercial projects, according to the Palestinian weekly
newspaper, The Jerusalem Times today.
</P>
<P>
The new center is being built on an area of 40,000 square
meters. It will include a shopping center with a parking space,
escalators, gardens, offices and apartment units.
</P>
<P>
The project will create over 500 jobs for engineers,
technicians, construction workers and other manual laborers.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- There are 20 banks with 78 branches currently
operating in the Palestinian territories, The Jerusalem Times
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Out of these branches, 52 have been founded in the West Bank
and the remaining 26 in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
Among the 20 banks, eight are Palestinian banks that have
been licensed by the Palestinian Monetary Authority (PMA). Out
of these, four began their operation this year.
</P>
<P>
The eight Palestinian banks include two commercial and two
Islamic banks, with the rest being designed for either general
purpose or investment.
</P>
<P>
There are also eight Jordanian banks, two Egyptian ones, an
Israeli one and an international bank, all operating in the
Palestinian self-rule areas.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The Offset Program Department of the Kuwaiti
Finance Ministry signed an offset memorandum with the Italian
company of Oerlikon Contraves today, a press release by the
ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The release said that under the memorandum the company is
obligated to invest a total of 675,000 U.S. dollars in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait has launched the counter-trade offset program since July
1992 which requires all winning foreign tenders from the country,
especially military contracts, equal to or more than 3.3 million
dollars to invest back 30 percent of the contract value in Kuwaiti
economic and development plans.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait so far has signed more than a dozen of offset agreements
with foreign companies, bringing the investment obligations to
the country to several hundred million dollars.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran and Georgia signed here today a memorandum of
understanding on cooperation in the energy sector.
</P>
<P>
The official Iranian news agency IRNA reported that visiting
Georgian energy minister David Zubita Shvili expressed his
country's interest in buying 150 megawatts of electricity from
Iran.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also reached agreement on the establishment of a
joint company which will start its activities by the end of
August, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The company is to handle construction, repair and
reconstruction work in the Georgian energy network and to
participate in international tenders of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Thailand has officially notified Oman of its
decision to postpone the purchase of liquefied natural gas (LNG)
as tentatively agreed upon by the two sides in 1996, the Omani
news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Thai Industry Minister Korn Dhabbharagnsri said he wanted more
time for "checking and research" because when he assumed office
the initial deal had been nearly completed, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
The two countries signed in August last year a preliminary
agreement, under which Petroleum Authority of Thailand would buy
2.2 million tonnes of Oman's LNG annually, beginning from 2003.
</P>
</TEXT>
