<HEADLINE> World Bank Approves 125 Million Dollars Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Pei Shanqin)
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank's Board of
Directors has approved 125 million US Dollars financial support
to Tanzania for the Country Assistance Strategy and Structural
Adjustment Project.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank resident representative in the country, Ron
Brigish told reporters here today that the Board of Directors
endorsed the financial support last Friday after extensive
discussions at its headquarters in Washington D.C. of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
"The endorsement for the funds is something which gives us
confidence to work comfortably," said Brigish.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank official said some 75 million US Dollars out of
the lump sum had been earmarked for the National Bank of Commerce
(NBC) restructuring program and other business.
</P>
<P>
He explained that out of the total amount to be disbursed for
NBC, some 25 million US Dollars would be disbursed in the next
financial year (1997/98).
</P>
<P>
Brigish clarified that the disbursement of the remaining 50
million US Dollars would depend on adequate progress in the
restructuring process.
</P>
<P>
The world Bank official said the international financial
institution had also given more time to the government to work
out the necessary preparations for the restructuring process of
the NBC.
</P>
<P>
"The World Bank has agreed to give more time the government to
continue with its preparations and no deadline has been set,"
explained Brigish.
</P>
<P>
He dismissed allegations that the World Bank was pressurizing
the government to restructure the NBC. However, he said, it was
absolutely necessary and was part of the bank's condition.
</P>
<P>
The bank official said the board of the bank had allocated
some 25 million US Dollars for the communication sector, while
some 15 million US Dollars had been earmarked for liberalization
of petroleum products services and 10 million US Dollars was set
for improving social sectors services.
</P>
<P>
He said during the discussions, the board challenged the
Tanzanian government to ensure that its policies were designed to
enable the country to become economically self-sustaining.
</P>
<P>
Brigish said the bank's Board of Directors also emphasized the
government to continue with its endeavors to reduce dependence on
foreign aids by ensuring that there was a sound management of the
economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
