British Prime Minister Tony Blair, who broke off low-level
contacts with Sinn Fein last week after the IRA killed two police
officers in Northern Ireland, urged Saturday the IRA to deliver a
truce so as to gain a seat in the multi-party peace talks on
Northern Ireland peace process.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein is barred from the multi-party discussions because
the IRA refuses to restore a truce it broke in February 1996.
</P>
<P>
Mowlam also said Britain and Ireland were working very hard to
reach an agreement which would be discussed in the talks.
</P>
<P>
Martin McGuinness, chief negotiator for Sinn Fein, said
yesterday the disarmament issue remained a major obstacle in peace
process. 
