<HEADLINE> Trade Between Tanzania, S. Africa Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's exports to South
Africa rose from nil in 1994 to 2.4 billion Tanzania Shillings
(about 4 million US Dollars) last year, meanwhile the country
imported goods worth 27.7 billions Shillings (about 46 million US
Dollars) from S. Africa.
</P>
<P>
Minister for Industries and Trade William Shija told the
National Assembly in Dodoma, central Tanzania today that since
the two countries resumed trade ties in 1994, commercial success
has also been registered with S. African investors shipping
capital into Tanzania and taking up business in various sectors
of the economy.
</P>
<P>
He said, for example, over past two years, six South African
companies have set up branches in Tanzania or entered into
commercial partnership with Tanzanian business establishments.
</P>
<P>
Shija said, however, that Tanzania stood to gain
technologically from S. Africa's technological advancement. "The
arrival of S. African companies in this country should give us
the benefit of technology transfer and should help in
strengthening our private sector," he noted.
</P>
<P>
While exporting to South Africa cashewnuts, cotton, sisal
products, cotton cake, precious stones, aluminium products and
textiles, Tanzania imports machinery, electric components,
medical drugs, and various types of raw materials, the minister
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
