<HEADLINE> Arab Agencies Call for Stringent Anti-Narcotics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The 11th Conference of the Arab
Anti-narcotic Agencies has recommended stringent measures to
combat drug smuggling.
</P>
<P>
This came in a statement released today by the Tunis-based
Secretariat of the Arab Interior Ministers' Council at the
conclusion of the conference in Jeddah, Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
The conference called for severe border control among Arab
states, particularly those serving as drug-dealing centers or
transit routes for drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
The conference also urged the ratification by all the 22
council members of an Arab anti-drug agreement.
</P>
<P>
So far, ten Arab states have ratified the agreement which was
concluded by the Arab Interior Ministers' Council in 1994 and went
into effect in mid-1996.
</P>
<P>
Concluding its current three-day session today, the conference
also called the council members' to adopt a single stance at the
extraordinary U.N. General Assembly session this year on combating
narcotics.
</P>
<P>
The conference requested the secretariat to work out unified
plans to enforce restrictions on the production, import and
export of basic chemicals used in making narcotics, as well as to
keep the public aware of the dangers and abuses of drugs. 
</P>
