<HEADLINE> Greenpeace to Sue UK Govt over Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Greenpeace spokesperson Mirella
Lindenfels said today the environmental group is seeking to take
the British Government to court this week over plans to open up
Atlantic waters for oil exploration.
</P>
<P>
"We intend to lodge papers sometime this week to ask leave from
the High Court to pursue the case," Lindenfels said.
</P>
<P>
She explained that the government had failed to apply the
European Habitats Directive when it awarded permits in the 17th
offshore licensing round for oil exploration, mainly in the
Rockall Trough west of the Hebrides and north of the Shetland
Islands earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Last March, Greenpeace had applied for all the licenses with
the intention of turning the 35,000 square km into a marine
wildlife sanctuary. The bid was rejected by the Department of
Trade and Industry (DTI) and the licenses were granted to 14 oil
companies.
</P>
<P>
If the High Court grants Greenpeace leave, the case will go to
court and the group will call for the oil exploration to be
suspended until the case is concluded.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, greenpeace activists occupied the London
office of U.S. oil company Conoco, which among others was awarded
the right to explore for oil in the 17th licensing round, for
about four hours.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Department of Trade and Industry said the
government's position was to go ahead with the oil plan and it
would go to court if it had to. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
