<HEADLINE> Egypt Welcomes U.S. Peace Stance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
said today Egypt welcomed the U.S. government's stance on the
Mideast peace process that reaffirmed the importance of abiding by
previous agreements.
</P>
<P>
Telling reporters here, the Egyptian top diplomat echoed the
recent remarks by U.S Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on the
importance of abiding by the Palestinian-Israeli deals and staying
away from unilateral measures to prejudice the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Albright's remarks followed an Arab uproar over a
U.S. Congressional vote on June 10 recognizing Jerusalem as the
Jewish eternal capital despite the Palestinian claim of the city's
eastern sector as their future capital.
</P>
<P>
"I consider Albright's remarks as basis for pushing forward the
Mideast peace process," Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
Unlike her predecessors who had frequented the Middle East,
Albright is yet to pay a visit to the region since she took
office in January.
</P>
<P>
The Arab countries have been urging the U.S., the main sponsor
of the peace process and the only country that has a leverage over
Israel, to put up its pressure on the Jewish state for an early
resumption of the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Moussa declined to say if Egyptian presidential political
advisor Osama el-Baz is to launch a new mediation tour to the
Palestinian self-rule area and Israel later this week.
</P>
<P>
But the Egyptian Middle East News Agency quoted informed
sources as saying Sunday that Baz will travel to Israel by the
weekend, after his rounds of shuttle diplomacy between the
Palestinians and Israelis during the past month have failed to
produce a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
Saying that Cairo wants to overcome, rather than ignore,
difficulties on the road of peace, Moussa maintained that the
Egyptian diplomacy aims to create an atmosphere favorable for
salvaging the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
"The Egyptian role has never slowed down in any stage of
Arab-Israeli talks and Egypt will seize any opportunity to rescue
the negotiations from the present pitfall," he said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has intensified its efforts at mediation after
U.S. peace envoy Dennis Ross failed to restart the talks that
broke down in March after Israel began the construction of a
Jewish housing project in Arab East Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
