<HEADLINE> Inter-African Force, French Troops Attack Mutineers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The Chadian-led Inter-African
intervention force, backed by French troops, attacked a major
barracks of the mutineers in the Central African Republic's
capital, Bangui, this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The Agence France-Presse (AFP) reported that the soldiers of
the Inter-African Mission of Supervision of the Accords of Bangui
(MISAB) launched a mopping-up operation against the mutineers in
the southwestern "pro-mutiny" districts of Bangui, after pounding
the Kassai camp of the rebels with heavy artillery fire.
</P>
<P>
French troops also struck the rebels from military helicopters
flying above the camp, after four shells fell today at the French
embassy without causing any casualty or damage, reported AFP.
</P>
<P>
The latest attack brought the number of people killed to about
50 and those wounded to 100, after fighting broke out last Friday
between the mutineers and the MISAB forces.
</P>
<P>
MISAB soldiers "cleaned up" all resistance pockets of the
rebels in the districts of Kouanga, Bacongo, Kpetene, Petevo and
Sica-1 in southwestern and central Bangui.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the president of the International Follow-up
Committee of the Accords of Bangui, General Amadou Toumani Toure
of Mali, is expected to arrive in Bangui Tuesday from Libreville,
where he held talks today with Gabonese President Omar Bongo, who
heads a mediation mission of several African heads of state for
the Central Africa crisis. 
</P>
