<HEADLINE> Supreme Court Ruling Upholds Sexual Predator Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Supreme Court ruled
today that states can keep violent sexual predators locked up
after they serve their prison sentences even if they are not
mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
In a decision that bodes well for the country's "Megan's laws,"
the court has reversed a lower-court ruling that struck down
Kansas's Sexually Violent Predator Act as unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
In effect, the act allowed the state to confine sexual
predators to a mental institution after they served sentences, but
without any further crimes or convictions.
</P>
<P>
The Kansas Supreme Court's law case could come this week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
