<HEADLINE> Turkish PM Designate Holds Talks for New Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister designate
Mesut Yilmaz today began rounds of hard talks in effort to form a
new coalition government.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz, chairman of the second largest Motherland Party
(ANAP), was appointed by President Suleyman Demirel to set up
a new government following the resignation of Prime Minister
Necmettin Erbakan on June 18.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz met with leaders of several political parties,
including Tansu Ciller, chairwoman of the True Path Party (DYP)
and also deputy prime minister of the caretaker government.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters at a press conference here, Yilmaz said
that the new government would be one of cohesion and
reconciliation, adding it aimed to solve the problems of the
country within democracy.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that he would not hold talks with the Welfare
Party (RP) led by Erbakan and the Grand Unity Party (BBP) led by
Muhsin Yazicioglu.
</P>
<P>
BBP, which has eight seats in the parliament, had said that it
favored a DYP-led coalition government.
</P>
<P>
For the time being, Yilmaz has enjoyed 265 votes of the
parliament, not enough to survive a possible vote of confidence in
the 550-seat parliament with a vacancy of two.
</P>
<P>
This means Yilmaz has to win over at least nine DYP deputies to
secure the new coalition government, political analysts said.
</P>
<P>
If the new government failed to win a vote of confidence in the
parliament, the mandate to form a government will naturally go to
Ciller, whose party ranks third in the legislature.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan resigned under the pressure from both the military and
his junior coalition partner DYP who criticized the government's
failure in curbing the rapidly expanding fundamentalist force in
the secular republic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
