<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Opposes Cyprus EU Membership Application </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Minister Tansu
Ciller today reiterated Turkey's opposition for Cyprus' EU
membership application.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement issued by the Foreign Ministry, Ciller
said that Cyprus cannot be admitted to the European bloc before
Turkey becomes a full EU member state.
</P>
<P>
She made the statement as Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides
and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash will begin a
face-to-face talks in New York on July 9.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has repeatly voiced its concern over unilateral EU
talks with Cyprus on the island country's membership issue,
saying the Cypriot government has no right to represent Turkish
Cypriots living in the north.
</P>
<P>
Ciller, also deputy prime minister of the caretaker coalition
government, said that this was clearly stipulated in the Cyprus
agreements signed in 1959 and 1960, which gave guarantor status
to Turkey, Greece as well as Britain.
</P>
<P>
"In this context, we have repeatedly emphasized that Cyprus
cannot become a member of the EU before Turkey," Ciller said.
</P>
<P>
She added that the Cypriot government could not start its
negotiations unilaterally with the EU officials before the
Cyprus problem was resolved.
</P>
<P>
"Only after an agreement has been reached on the solution of
the Cyprus question can a joint delegation, in which the Turkish
Cypriot and Greek Cypriot communities are represented on an equal
basis, take part in accession negotiations with the EU," said
Ciller.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said that she had transmitted this
opinion to both Britain and the Netherlands which currently
holds the EU presidency.
</P>
<P>
Turkish troops landed on Cyprus in 1974 in response to a
pro-Greek coup, dividing the East Mediterranean island into Greek
and Turkish communities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
