<HEADLINE> Chinese Photo Exhibition on Hong Kong Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 23 (Xinhua) -- A week-long photo exhibition
showing Hong Kong's history and Chinese government's measures to
guarantee the stability and prosperity of Hong Kong after its
return to China from British rule opened at the Center of Kuwaiti
Fine Arts here today.
</P>
<P>
The opening ceremony of the exhibition which starts on the eve
of Hong Kong's return to China on July 1, was inaugurated by
Kuwaiti Minister of Social Affairs and Labor Ahmed Al-Kulaib and
Chinese Ambassador to Kuwait Zhang Zhixiang.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition, entitled "Hong Kong's Past, Present and
Future," was held jointly by the Chinese Embassy in Kuwait and
Kuwaiti Ministry of Social Affairs and Labor.
</P>
<P>
A total of 99 pictures taken by Chinese and foreign
photographers are on display.
</P>
<P>
The photos cover the history of the Hong Kong people's struggle
against the British rule during the past one-and-half century.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition also shows the various measures taken by the
Chinese government to guarantee Hong Kong's smooth transition and
continued prosperity and stability in accordance with the
principles of "one country, two systems" and "Hong Kong people
governing Hong Kong".
</P>
<P>
Al-Kulaib, in a brief interview with Xinhua after the
ceremony, congratulated the Chinese people on Hong Kong's return
to the motherland and expressed his good wishes that "Hong Kong
would become more prosperous and beautiful" in the future.
</P>
<P>
He said the collection of photos gave a view of Hong Kong's
past under the British colonial rule and helped people understand
Hong Kong's present and future.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Embassy would also organize a film festival in
cooperation with Kuwait Film Club and hold a grand reception on
June 30 to commemorate the historical event, Ambassador Zhang told
Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
He said Kuwait is soon to open a consulate to look after
its trade interests in Hong Kong and there would be an exchange
of trade missions between China and Kuwait in the near future.
</P>
</TEXT>
