<HEADLINE> Business Leaders in California Positive on Hong Kong's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 23 (Xinhua)--Hong Kong's return to China will
create a new era not only of relations between China's inland and
Hong Kong, but also of Pacific Rim trade and investment, according
to a business leader here.
</P>
<P>
"You will find a strengthening of China's economic engagement to
Asia as well as the rest of the world," said Richard King, a
founder of the Hong Kong Association of Southern California and
known as one of the pillars of Los Angeles international trade
community.
</P>
<P>
King, president of the King International Group, a consultant
company promoting Pacific Rim business relations, said that he was
very positive about China's "takeover" of Hong Kong. "I found most
of the business people I talked to are also positive about the
takeover," he said.
</P>
<P>
He has spent a lot of time over the past few weeks on giving
lectures on the transition of power in Hong Kong to various
organizations in southern California, trying to put the event in
perspective and explain the Chinese cultural aspect of it. The
average Americans, he said, came to know the transition by reading
newspapers which tend to pick up unrealistic issues. "We should
make people better informed and I don't think our economic
relations should be dictated by the media," he said.
</P>
<P>
China is the second largest trading partner of California
with the seventh largest economy of the world. According to
preliminary statistics, in the first quarter of this year,
California's exports to China's mainland and Hong Kong
respectively increased by 14 percent and 20 percent. China and
Hong Kong together brought 1.4 billion US dollars worth of goods
from California.
</P>
<P>
Headquartered in Los Angeles, King's company has affiliates
in Hong Kong, Taipei, Tokyo and Chongqing in southwest China.
</P>
<P>
King predicted that Hong Kong's transition will strengthen
China's economy and greatly influence southern China which is
already a huge market.
</P>
<P>
He said that American and Chinese firms can team-up not only
in Asia but also in central America and Africa.
</P>
<P>
"That will be an exciting development and Hong Kong's return
might contribute to it," said King, who believed that economic
collaboration could increase mutual understanding.
</P>
<P>
King's views are shared by John Coleman, a lawyer and
president of the Hong Kong Association of Southern California,
an organization of over 700 corporation members aimed at
promoting business with Hong Kong and southern China.
</P>
<P>
According to Coleman, the business community in southern
California has been very positive about Hong Kong's transfer.
"I think it is not only a great opportunity for China and Hong
Kong, but also for the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Confidence in Hong Kong is strong," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
