<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Criminal Use of Guns Drops in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The criminal use of guns appears to
be declining in Canada, despite a wide-spread belief to the
contrary, a report said today.
</P>
<P>
An exception is in Canada's three largest cities of Toronto,
Montreal and Vancouver, where firearms are the weapons most
frequently involved in homicides.
</P>
<P>
Across the country, the use of firearms in homicides has
gradually decreased since 1975, according to a study by the
Canadian Centre for Justice Statistics.
</P>
<P>
And the use of firearms in spousal homicides also declined
slightly, from 36 percent of all victims from 1985 to 1994 to 28
percent by 1995.
</P>
<P>
More significant, the use of firearms declined in types of
violent crimes that are on the rise, mostly notably robbery.
</P>
<P>
"While the proportion of all weapons involved in robberies has
remained relatively stable over the years, the involvement of
firearms has decreased by 41 percent since 1975," the study said.
</P>
<P>
Of about 1,100 deaths from gunshots in 1995, 13 percent were
homicides, while 81 percent were suicides and 6 percent were
attributed to accidents.
</P>
<P>
The study echoed earlier surveys that found the rate of violent
crime in Canada, after nearly doubling between 1975 and 1992, is
on a downward trend. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
