<HEADLINE> French PM Unhappy with Denver Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 24 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin
today expressed deep dissatisfaction over the Denver G-8 summit
held last weekend in the U.S. Rocky Mountain city, which he
described as "a circumstance not so comfortable for our country
and Europe."
</P>
<P>
Without naming the United States, Jospin said that he felt a
"certain tendency of hegemony" from the host of the summit. He
also deplored that France and Europe failed to convey a strong
enough message at the summit.
</P>
<P>
"We feel a certain tendency of hegemony which is not strictly
identifiable with the simple exercise of responsibilities of a
great power, even though a friend," said Jospin in front of the
parliament deputies.
</P>
<P>
He said that although he himself did not take part in the
summit, he asked Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine and Finance
Minister Dominique Strauss-Kahn to accompany President Jacques
Chirac on the trip, because he did not want to "leave (Chirac)
alone in this circumstance which is not so comfortable to our
country and Europe."
</P>
<P>
"Europe, and the capacity of France, and my government and
this (parliamentary) majority should take up the challenge that
next time, the concerns of Europe should be taken into account
with more force," said Jospin. 
</P>
