<HEADLINE> France in Favor of International Force for Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 24 (Xinhua) -- France today expressed its
willingness to send an international peace-keeping force to the
Republic of Congo to help end the factional fighting in the
country.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry spokesman Yves Doutriaux told reporters
here that the deployment of an international force
alone would not be enough to resolve the crisis in the republic.
</P>
<P>
"But it could, in the framework of a negotiated settlement,
contribute, in a decisive manner, to consolidating a peaceful way
out and a lasting ceasefire," he added.
</P>
<P>
He also confirmed that fighting in the Congolese capital
Brazzaville between troops led by President Pascal Lissouba and
militia loyal to former president Denis Sassou-Nguesso died down
today after Monday's violent shooting and shelling.
</P>
<P>
The crisis in Congo erupted in 1992 when a coalition government
led by Lissouba, head of the Pan-African Union for Social
Democracy, and Sassou-Nguesso, head of the Congolese Labor Party,
spilt due to sharp differences over power distribution.
</P>
<P>
Factional fighting broke out in 1993 when Sassou-Nguesso
refused to accept the result of a fresh election in which Lissouba
won and established a new government.
</P>
<P>
Fresh fighting erupted on June 5 when forces loyal to
Lissouba surrounded Sassou-Nguesso's home to disarm his private
militia ahead of the planned presidential elections on July 27.
</P>
<P>
Both sides agreed to a three-day ceasefire last Tuesday and
to extend the truce for another seven days last Friday.
</P>
<P>
However, sporadic fighting resumed on Monday after mortars were
fired on the parliament building in Brazzaville, aiming to prevent
deputies from attending a meeting called by Lissouba to review the
conflict with Sassou-Nguesso. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
