<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Reaffirms Stance on Mass Destruction Weapons, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian government, in a reply
today to a statement issued at the summit of eight developed
nations (G-8), reaffirmed its stance on issues of weapons of mass
destruction and terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi declared that Iran
is opposed to all sorts of terrorism but it will continue to
support the people of south Lebanon until the liberation of the
area from the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian spokesman termed the advice by the summit in the
U.S. city of Denver, Colorado to ban military cooperation with
Iran as "an excuse to ban the transfer of technology to developing
countries."
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi said that Iran has no need for the help which the
summit referred to as the nuclearization of Iran.
</P>
<P>
"Iran considers all kinds of control and monopoly by the
industrialized nations as efforts to create a rift between
developing and developed countries and rejects it as being
contrary to all international norms and conventions," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Iran has proved its commitment to
international norms and its opposition to any investment on the
production of all weapons of mass destruction by signing the
international convention on banning chemical weapons and its
subsequent ratification by its parliament.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he added, "Iran invites all developing countries
to demonstrate greater solidarity to halt such bans and
monopoly."
</P>
<P>
Describing Iran as the main victim of terrorism sponsored by
"certain states," the spokesman said Iran calls on "these states
to seriously avoid selective approach to the phenomenon of
terrorism and not to allow supporters of terrorist organizations
by using their discriminatory double standards to promote inhumane
and violent methods."
</P>
<P>
The G-8 group, comprising the United States, Britain, France,
Germany, Italy, Canada, Japan and Russia, discussed, in its
two-day annual session ending Sunday, voiced their determination
to fight terrorism and oppose concessions of terrorist demands.
</P>
<P>
He underlined that Iran attaches great importance to stability
and security in the Middle East and considers the "Zionist
regime" as the "instigator of crisis in the region and the main
agent of insecurity and state-sponsored terrorism."
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi called on the industrialized countries to stop using
"double standards in arming Israel with destructive weapons as
well as bring pressure on the regime occupying Qods (Jerusalem) to
honor its commitments to international norms particularly
regarding the control of its atomic weapons centers and make the
region free of mass destruction weapons."
</P>
<P>
He was quoted by the official Iranian news agency IRNA as
saying that the summit leaders neglected what he termed as the
expansionist policies of Israel in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman criticized the G-8 leaders for having acted
against U.N. resolutions and the rights of the Muslims and the
Arabs, calling for the complete restoration of the rights of the
Palestinians and the liberation of all occupied Arab territories
including the Golan Heights of Syria and south Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
