<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Hong Kong Executive Council Holds Last Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The British Hong Kong Executive
Council held its last meeting here today following the last
meeting of the Hong Kong Legislative Council that opened Monday.
</P>
<P>
The meetings for both councils indicate that the two major
bodies of the British Hong Kong political structure are ceasing
their operation.
</P>
<P>
The Executive Council's meeting lasted two and a half hours and
it only opened to a few assigned news media for photographing.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong Governor Chris Patten and other members of the
Executive Council attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Executive Council was the top decision-making body and all
of its members were appointed by the Hong Kong governor.
</P>
<P>
The Legislative Council's function was to formulate laws and
control public spending.
</P>
<P>
The existing Legislative Council was the outcome of the
"Constitutional Package" pursued unilaterally by the British Hong
Kong Authorities.
</P>
<P>
Due to the British side's destruction of the "through train"
arrangement, the existing Legislative Council of Hong Kong will
cease its operation on June 30, according to the decision made by
the Ninth Meeting of the Standing Committee of the 8th Chinese
National People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
China will resume its exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong in
seven days. To date, the executive, legislative and judiciary
bodies of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) have
been formed.
</P>
<P>
The Chief Executive of the HKSAR, 23 principal officials of the
HKSAR government, members of the HKSAR Executive Council and
Provisional Legislative Council, and Chief Justice and permanent
judges of the Court of Final Appeal as well Chief Judge of the
High Court will be sworn in on July 1.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Third Cable-Stayed Bridge Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai's third cable-stayed
bridge across the Huangpu River opened to traffic today.
</P>
<P>
The Xupu Bridge is 6,017 meters long and 35.95 meters wide and
was built in the same style as the Nanpu and Yangpu bridges.
</P>
<P>
The new bridge has eight lanes, two more than Nanpu and Yangpu,
and is designed for speeds of 80 km/h.
</P>
<P>
Xupu is a part of the 98-km outer ring road that is still under
constuction, and an important section of the highway running from
Hongqiao International Airport to Pudong International Airport
that is in the planning stages at the Pudong New Area.
</P>
<P>
The bridge is expected to improve traffic conditions on both
sides of the Huangpu River.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
