<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Financial Status Guaranteed by Basic Law and Sino- </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The successful implementation of
the Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR) and the Sino-British Joint Declaration will safeguard Hong
Kong's current status as an international financial center.
</P>
<P>
The remarks came from Rafael Hui Si-yan, secretary for
Financial Services in the current and future Hong Kong
governments, at a press briefing in the Hong Kong Convention and
Exhibition Center here today.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law of the Hong Kong SAR stipulates that after its
return to China, Hong Kong will maintain its status as an
international financial center. The markets for foreign exchange,
gold, securities and futures will continue to open with a free
flow of capital, and the Hong Kong dollar will continue to
circulate and remain freely convertible.
</P>
<P>
"All these stipulations will guarantee Hong Kong's status as an
international financial center," Hui said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the future HKSAR government will strive to
keep its commitment to the principle of non-interference in the
operation of the financial market, while making every effort to
provide a business environment that is open, flexible, fair and in
compliance with the international standard.
</P>
<P>
"To enhance Hong Kong's competitiveness, the SAR government
will further improve the mechanism of settlement in the banks, set
up a complete financial supervisory set-up, and expand cooperation
with securities exchanges in other countries and regions," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he added, the government will also try to change the
way of flow in the bonds market, to promote further development of
the insurance sector.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that the rapid economic growth in the
Asia-Pacific region, especially in China's interior areas, will
provide more opportunities of development for the financial sector
in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, Hong Kong is also obliged to play a more important
role in the modernization drive of China's interior areas, by
making greater efforts to raise funds for the economic development
of the interior areas," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said that to date 29 companies from the interior
areas have been listed on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, and
arrangements are being made for matters relating to the listing of
five other companies.
</P>
<P>
"The Hong Kong Monetary Authority and the People's Bank of
China are now discussing their cooperation in the field of
settlement," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
