<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Minister Leaves for Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
left here today to attend the Damascus Declaration foreign
ministers' discussions on the establishment of an Arab common
market.
</P>
<P>
The eight foreign ministers of the Damascus Declaration
members' will hold their 15th routine meeting at Syrian
Mediterranean city of Latakia tomorrow with a full political and
economic agenda.
</P>
<P>
An Arab common market would start with Egypt, Syria and the
six-nation Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) while leaving the door
open for other countries to join, according to previous
discussions and arrangements.
</P>
<P>
In a pre-departure statement, Moussa voiced hope that this
session would further help consolidate Arab action, region
stability and the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Latakia meeting would also discuss Turkey's incursion in
northern Iraq against separatist Kurds and its military
cooperation with Israel, which has also raised concern among the
Arab states.
</P>
<P>
Moussa will make a stopover in the Jordanian capital of Amman,
where he will deliver a lecture in a seminar to be organized by
the UN-affiliated Higher Leaders Academy.
</P>
<P>
The Damascus Declaration alliance, which was formed in the
immediate aftermath of the 1991 Gulf War to develop security and
political links, groups Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates,
Kuwait, Qatar, Bahrain, Oman, Syria and Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
