<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Help Small Businesses With New </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 24 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Department of
Trade and Industry (DTI) is planning to replace its existing
export assistance scheme with a new export scheme, hoping to add
benefits for small businesses, local press reports said today.
</P>
<P>
The the new export scheme, the Export Marketing and Investment
Assistance Scheme (EMIA) is aimed to compensate exporters for
costs incurred in developing export markets, said DTI Assistant
Director Mohammed Vawda at a function in Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
The EMIA, divided into eight sub-schemes to assist exporters
in areas ranging from export market research, offshore
exhibitions, and attracting foreign investors, is expected to
come into full operation early August.
</P>
<P>
The project will offer participants benefits including
subsidized airline tickets, a daily subsistence allowance for
overseas travel, payment of transport while in the export market,
and grants to set up industry export councils offshore.
</P>
<P>
Vawda said attracting local enterprises to attend
international trade exhibitions is an important and popular
benefit offered by the DTI.
</P>
<P>
However, the benefits provided by EMIA will only be available
to exporters of goods of South African origin, and will not be
provided to service industries, said Vawda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
