<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Meets With Russian First Deputy Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Premier Li Lanqing, meeting
with Russian First Deputy Prime Minister Boris Nemtsov here today,
said that bilateral relations have developed smoothly since the
meeting of Premier Li Peng and Russia's Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin last December.
</P>
<P>
Nemtsov is here to make preparations for the second regular
meeting between Li and Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
Li said that President Jiang Zemin's Russia visit in April was
successful and that the strategic and cooperative partnership has
made new progress. This is significant for the long-term
friendship and mutual beneficial cooperation between the two
countries, he added.
</P>
<P>
China places great importance on cooperation with Russia, Li
said, and political, economic, and trade ties are a major part of
bilateral relations, and that economic and trade ties are the
basis for political relations.
</P>
<P>
Li said that to increase bilateral trade to 20 billion US
dollars by the end of the the century, the two should first
implement the agreements reached at Li and Chernomyrdin's meeting
in December.
</P>
<P>
At same time we should take advantage of the economies and
geography of the two countries, tapping the cooperative potential,
seeking new channels and ways, and improve economic and trade
relations between the two sides to meet Sino-Russian strategic and
cooperative partnership demands.
</P>
<P>
Nemtsov said that he was pleased to have a chance to visit
China at this time on the eve of the return of Hong Kong to the
motherland and expressed his pleasure with the smooth development
of bilateral relations. He said that Russia places great
importance on its relations with China, and bilateral cooperation,
and hopes that the two countries can work together to advance
bilateral economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He said that bilateral trade volume is less than 7 billion US
dollars at present, and that this is very small and not fitting
for the status of the two countries as big powers,
</P>
<P>
Saying that the two countries' aim in bilateral trade of 20
billion US dollars by the year 2000 is high, he noted that the two
countries will try their best to reach that goal. Russia and China
should increase their cooperation in the fields of energy and
fuels, and engage in some major projects.
</P>
<P>
Nemtsov arrived here Monday at the invitation of vice-premier
Li Lanqing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong to Launch China-Affiliated Corporation Derivatives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Stock Exchange of Hong Kong
and the Hong Kong Futures Exchange said here today that they will
begin trading in stock options and stock futures on the shares of
two China-affiliated corporations in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
The two companies, China Resources Enterprises and Shanghai
Industrial Holdings, are the first non-Hang Seng Index component
companies to have exchange-traded stock options and stock futures
introduced on their shares.
</P>
<P>
"We are pleased with the joint effort of the two exchanges in
launching these products. They will meet investors' demand and
enhance Hong Kong's role in the regional derivatives market," said
Dr Edgar Cheng, chairman of the stock exchange.
</P>
<P>
Frank Wong, chairman of the futures exchange, said introduction
of these new derivatives demonstrates an ability to respond
swiftly to new trading opportunities.
</P>
<P>
"Our responsiveness to changing market conditions is important
to Hong Kong's ability to maintain its leadership in
exchange-traded equity derivative products in Asia," he said.
</P>
<P>
Introduction of derivatives on the shares of the two companies
 will bring the number of stock options classes traded at the
stock exchange to 15, and the number of stock futures contracts
traded at the futures exchange to seven. 
</P>
</TEXT>
