<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior Government Official Confident in Hong Kong's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Nicholas Ng Wing Fui, Secretary for Constitutional Affairs,
told a press briefing held here that the Sino-British Joint
Declaration is far-sighted in concept, with emphasis placed on
maintaining Hong Kong's vigor and characteristics, and on making
sure that Hong Kong will implement the policy of "one country, two
systems," "Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong," and a "high
degree of autonomy" after its return to China.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is under such a general framework that Hong
Kong will continue to enjoy long-term prosperity and stability.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary told Chinese and foreign reporters that the
establishment of the Sino-British Joint Liaison Group (JLG) was
intended to facilitate the consultation between the Chinese and
British governments on the implementation of the Joint
Declaration, the discussions about matters related to Hong Kong's
handover, and the exchange of views on matters decided upon by the
two sides.
</P>
<P>
Since the establishment of the JLG in 1985, the Chinese and
British sides have reached many agreements falling into four
categories, i.e., maintaining the rule of law, the guarantee of
human rights, improving construction of the economic foundation
and the related systems, and ensuring the smooth transfer of
power. 
</P>
</TEXT>
