<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Problem For Many Chinese Elderly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- About 80 percent of the elderly
Chinese suffer from the bone disease osteoporosis and that females
are more susceptible, a Chinese doctor told a symposium on
osteoporosis marking the first World Osteoporosis Day today.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Liu Zhonghou, chairman of the Osteoporosis Committee of
the China Gerontological Society, warned that because of the rapid
aging of the Chinese population, if effective disease-prevention
measures are not taken, the number of patients will increase to
some 110 million by 2010, and exceed 200 million by the middle of
the next century.
</P>
<P>
"At present, China has about 84 million osteoporosis sufferers
out of 110 million people 60 years of age or older, the largest
number in the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
Female osteoporosis patients are six times the number of males
in China, Liu said, and that as they get older their bones are
more susceptible to fractures.
</P>
<P>
But many people still underestimate the danger of the disease
and pay little attention to it. Studies show that only ten percent
of Asians know about osteoporosis, and the percentage is even
lower in China.
</P>
<P>
In order to increase people's awareness, the European
Foundation For Osteoporosis began World Osteoporosis Day
activities this year.
</P>
<P>
Experts have suggested old people eat more calcium-rich food,
get some sun, and do proper physical exercises to prevent the
disease.
</P>
<P>
The symposium was attended by some 500 experts from the China
Gerontological Society and the Chinese Medical Association. They
also discussed a new calcium-rich supplement developed by France's
Innotech International, sponsor of the symposium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
