<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Nominations for Indian Presidential Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Only Indian Vice-president K.R.
Narayanan and former chief election commissioner T.N. Seshan were
accepted as candidates for the country's 11th presidential
elections after all the nomination papers were scrutinized by the
Lok Sabha (the lower house of parliament) secretariat today.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports indicated that about five nominations including
those for Narayanan and Seshan might have the mandatory list of 50
proposers and 50 seconders from among the members of the electoral
college.
</P>
<P>
However, most of the some 60 nomination papers filed before the
deadline on Monday have been rejected as invalid except those for
Narayanan and Seshan after strict scrutiny today, Press Trust of
India said.
</P>
<P>
All the major political parties in the country, including the
ruling United Front, the Congress party and the Bharatiya Janata
Party, have filed nomination papers on behalf of Narayanan while
Seshan was supported by one regional party only.
</P>
<P>
The last date for withdrawal of candidatures is June 26. If
Seshan withdraws from the race, Narayanan, who is reportedly
enjoying about 87 percent support of the 4,848-strong electoral
college, will be declared elected without a contest.
</P>
<P>
If Seshan refuses to withdraw, members of the electoral
college will cast their votes on July 14.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
