<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Diplomat on Hong Kong Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, the 44-year-old career diplomat
said that the Australian government announced in late May it
accepts the passport of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region(HKSAR) for visa-issuing purposes, according it equivalent
treatment to that given to the British National (Overseas)
passport issued by Britain.
</P>
<P>
"This illustrates Australian government's support to the
confidence in Hong Kong's future", the consul general said.
</P>
<P>
As two important economic powerhouses in the Asia-Pacific
region, Australia and Hong Kong traditionally share important and
strong economic and trade relations. In 1996, Hong Kong was
Australia's fourth largest source and the sixth largest
destination of foreign investment, and the twelfth largest export
market. Meanwhile Australia was Hong Kong's eleventh largest
export market and the thirteenth largest source of imports.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are about 350 major Australian companies
operating in Hong Kong, plus smaller presence of other 1,000
Australian companies.
</P>
<P>
In a survey done last year, Australian business people in Hong
Kong overwhelmingly expressed the view that Hong Kong will
continue to be a good place to do business with and from.
</P>
<P>
"This shows the sentiment of the Australian business community
here is basically optimistic", noted Mr. Walsh, who has been
working in Hong Kong for two years.
</P>
<P>
"All the economic fundamentals of Hong Kong have been pointing
to the good outlook of Hong Kong," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Education and immigration are also two important fields for
exchange.
</P>
<P>
Australia is the second largest overseas destination only after
the United States for Hong Kong students seeking studies, with new
enrollment of about 4,000 each year.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are over 100,000 Hong Kongers settling down
in Australia, composing an important force of the local economy.
</P>
<P>
According to the consul general, while education exchanges have
remained strong, the applications for immigrating to Australia has
been declined in recent years.
</P>
<P>
"We believe the movement of people will remain as smooth as
before and this will be conducive to the economic and trade
exchanges," Walsh said.
</P>
<P>
Walsh, who has been to China at regular intervals with
high-ranking Australian government delegations since 1984, said he
has been deeply impressed by the "dramatic changes taking place in
China".
</P>
<P>
"The Sino-Australian relationship has been strengthened by our
prime Minister John Howard's recent visit to China and by Chinese
Vice Premier Zhu Rongji's visit to our country," he observed.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong, as an international business center, has always been
a link between Australia and the broad interior areas of China.
The handover will surely enhance the already strong
Sino-Australian bilateral relations, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"It's exciting and challenging to work in Hong Kong at this
period of time. With the number of Australians visiting Hong Kong
on constant rise, the work of the Consulate has been very busy,"
Walsh said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
