<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Language Course Increasingly Popular in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 24 (Xinhua) -- More than 20 middle-aged Hong
Kongers are learning and practising a song entitled "The
descendants of the Dragon" in standard Chinese (Putonghua) at a
civil servants' training center when the reporter entered the
room.
</P>
<P>
This is the ninth class for the intermediate Putonghua course
with three hours for each session, said Teng, a learner who is
working at the Rating and Valuation Department of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Teng said he couldn't speak a single word of Putonghua before
attending the course. Nevertheless, upon his graduation from the
junior class, he applied to study at the intermediate class and
has since made great progress.
</P>
<P>
It is worthwhile to learn Putonghua though it takes much time
and effort in the wake of the growing exchanges between Hong Kong
and the interior areas over recent years.
</P>
<P>
Wong Hsien-hua, director of the civil servants' training
section, said his section started to teach Putonghua back in 1982,
and then merely 40 people were recruited. As Hong Kong's
cooperation with the interior kept growing, 7,000 civil servants
came to study in 1996, and the number of trainees this year will
be same as last year.
</P>
<P>
Lam Wei-wen, a native of Macao who raised in Hong Kong, was
seen  practising hard with the song "A Crescent Moon". He said
that as a Chinese, he should be good at speaking the Chinese
language.
</P>
<P>
He told Xinhua that he often practises speaking Putonghua with
his wife and his son at home so as to speed up his learning in a
hope to communicate with people from interior areas at an early
date. 
</P>
</TEXT>
