<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Joins "Ottawa Process" to Ban Anti-Personnel Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 24 (Xinhua) -- France today formally joined the
international process to ban anti-personnel mines by the end of
the century, an initiative first proposed by Canada.
</P>
<P>
Joelle Bourgois, French ambassador to the International
Disarmament Conference in Geneva, signed a declaration in Brussels
today supporting the process which will lead to the signing
of an international treaty in December calling for a complete
ban on the mines, Agence France-Presse (AFP) reported.
</P>
<P>
France banned the production of anti-personnel mines in October
1996, but had failed to renounce the use of such mines by its
armed forces in security operations.
</P>
<P>
"France decided to renounce, from the coming into force of an
effective treaty and by the end of 1999 at the latest, the use of
the mines," Bourgois told a conference on the so-called Ottawa
Process attended by representatives from 161 countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
