<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Firm, Singapore Monetary Exchange Agree on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore International
Monetary Exchange (SIMEX) and Deutsche Borse AG, the holding
company of DTB Deutsche Terminborse, signed here today a linkage
agreement to trade DTB's BUND and BOBL futures and options as well
as SCHATZ futures contracts on the floor of the SIMEX.
</P>
<P>
SIMEX Chairman Victor Liew said at a press conference, "This
linkage with DTB represents an important step towards developing
European products for trading during the Asia-Pacific time zone."
</P>
<P>
"The linkage marks a historic milestone for SIMEX in its drive
to develop as a major center for risk management in its time zone
for the trading of interest rate products to complement its
Eurodollar and Euroyen interest rate contracts," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first such linkage between the DTB and an overseas
exchange," said Jorg Franke, member of Deutsche Borse's Executive
Board.
</P>
<P>
"It is significant in that it makes the way for DTB products to
be traded more intensively in the Asian time zone," he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement signed, the contracts traded on the SIMEX
floor will be fungible with the identical contracts traded at DTB.
All such contracts traded at SIMEX will be transferred at the end
of each trading day to DTB's clearing house for clearing.
</P>
<P>
As part of the cooperative arrangement, SIMEX will sponsor
DTB's application to the Monetary Authority of Singapore for
approval of the installation of DTB trading terminals in Singapore
for the exclusive utilization by SIMEX members which are
authorized by DTB to trade all the contracts listed by DTB on its
electronic trading system.
</P>
<P>
The linkage agreement will have an initial term of five years
with provisions for renewal for successive periods of five years.
</P>
<P>
Subject to regulatory approvals in Singapore and Germany, both
exchanges are working towards having the linkage arrangement put
in place by March 31 next year. But SIMEX officials said that they
believed it would be there much earlier.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
