<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Editor to be Tried on Espionage Charge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Judiciary Chief Ayatollah
Mohammad Yazdi today assured the European countries that an
editor of Iran's liberal magazine caught on charges of espionage
for Germany will have a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here, Yazdi rejected allegations
that the trial of Faraj Sarkouhi would be politicized because of
tensions in Tehran-Bonn ties in the aftermath of a verdict by a
German court holding top Iranian officials responsible for 1992
killing of four Kurdish dissidents in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
"Sarkouhi's case is merely a legal case. However, he will be
tried for a charge which is political," he said, adding that
Sarkouhi would definitely have a lawyer that would represent him
in court.
</P>
<P>
"We will not allow his trial to proceed if he does not have
an attorney to defend himself," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, Yazdi said that he could not confirm reports that
Sarkouhi's trial started Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Based on the instructions I have given, the court
responsible for Sarkouhi's trial is supposed to start the trial
any day," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I have been against delaying his trial. I think enough
information has been gathered and that the courts should not
have delayed the trial," he added.
</P>
<P>
Faraj Sarkouhi, editor of the Persian weekly Adineh, was
arrested along with his brother and two other smugglers while
attempting to make an illegal exit in Bushehr, a port city in
southern Iran in February.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Foreign Ministry had earlier rejected German
intervention in the arrest of the editor, who sought political
asylum in Sweden and Germany.
</P>
<P>
Mahmoud Mohammadi, spokesman of Iran's Foreign Ministry, said
"the arrest of the Iranian editor was simply a national issue
that did not warrant the interference of any foreign
government."
</P>
<P>
"The Islamic government could not possibly ignore its own
laws and principles when dealing with a person who has committed
heavy crimes," he said.
</P>
<P>
After Sarkouhi's disappearance in February this year,
international efforts spearheaded by Sweden and Germany have
been made to find out what has happened to the Iranian
journalist who has disappeared twice in three months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Will Observe Basic Law, Lee Kuan Yew Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's Senior Minister Lee
Kuan Yew expressed belief here today that the Chinese leadership
will observe the Sino-British Joint Declaration and the Basic Law
since this is in their own national interest.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a conference entitled "Countdown to 1997: Roadmap to
Hong Kong's Continued Prosperity," Lee said, "Those groups
pressing China on Hong Kong may find they have helped to frustrate
themselves, because China will make doubly sure it does not breach
the Joint Declaration and the Basic Law."
</P>
<P>
China is aware that the world is watching, and it will go out
of its way to show that Hong Kong can thrive and prosper
economically after its return to China, the senior minister said.
</P>
<P>
China wants a Hong Kong which can "attract funds from abroad
and be an interface with the international community," he noted.
</P>
<P>
For the next 50 years, Hong Kong will be a Special
Administrative Region (SAR) of China, enjoying full autonomy,
except in foreign and defense affairs, under "one country, two
systems," Lee said.
</P>
<P>
"The monetary system will remain intact, and the Hong Kong
people will determine fiscal policy. Equally, if not more
important, the entire legal system will continue to operate as
before," he continued.
</P>
<P>
Lee pointed out that currently, public confidence in the
economy is at a record high, as shown in a survey by Hong
Kong-based South China Morning Post in January this year, and this
confidence is reflected in the strength of the stock and property
markets.
</P>
<P>
The international community shares this confidence, he added.
In September, three months after the handover, the International
Monetary Fund and the World Bank will hold their joint annual
meeting in Hong Kong to lend their support for Hong Kong's future.
</P>
<P>
Li told the conference, "Over 800 multinational companies have
their regional headquarters in the city, one-third of them
established in the past five years. Another 1,500 overseas
companies have regional offices in Hong Kong. A recent survey
found that over 90 percent intend to stay after the handover."
</P>
<P>
"They cited favorable banking and financial facilities,
infrastructure and the tax regime as the top three attractions
and, clearly, they believe these attractions will remain
unchanged," Lee said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong residents who emigrated are coming back, he said. The
Hong Kong government has estimated that some 12 percent, or about
50,000, of the 420,000 people who left in the decade before 1994,
have returned, while foreigners are flowing in with their
families, he said.
</P>
<P>
Lee also declared Singapore's interest in Hong Kong and in the
Chinese mainland. As of the end of 1995, Singapore's private
sector investments in Hong Kong amounted to 4.5 billion US dollars
and, in the mainland, 2.1 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore government investment, on the other hand,
amounted to another 2 billion US dollars, adding Hong Kong and the
Chinese mainland together, he added.
</P>
<P>
If Singapore did not have confidence in the future of China, it
would not have been investing either in the mainland or in Hong
Kong, he said, adding, "We expect fair returns on these
investments."
</P>
<P>
The two-day conference was organized by the Far Eastern
Economic Review, Asia's premier business newsweekly.
</P>
<P>
S. Y. Chung, convenor of the Executive Council of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region, and Edgar Cheng, chairman of the
Stock Exchange of Hong Kong, among other speakers, addressed the
meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
