<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Business Leader Envisions More Opportunities for HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong is expected to
continue to benefit from the strengths that have led to its
success, and to be at "a pole position" to seize the opportunities
created by China's economic growth and opening-up.
</P>
<P>
This is the focal point of a written speech by Henry Tang,
chairman of the Federation of Hong Kong Industries and Member of
the Legislative Council, presented at a symposium on Hong Kong's
continued prosperity after its return to China on July 1 here
today.
</P>
<P>
"As part of one country with two systems," Tang noted, "Hong
Kong is poised to capture the best of both worlds, and that the
combination of Hong Kong's distinct strengths with those of the
mainland is likely to make us a formidable competitor for
companies based anywhere else in the world."
</P>
<P>
After its return to China, Tang said, Hong Kong's status as a
metropolitan heart of an increasingly affluent south China region
will be enhanced now that the barriers to official contact come
down, and both Hong Kong and other south China cities will benefit
from a joint planning of an industry base in the region, and
co-marshalling of the region's human and natural resources.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong will continue to play the role as the main source of
foreign capitals for the interior area, Tang observed, adding that
a growing number of mainland companies will seek to build links
with banks and investors in Hong Kong -- which "are among the main
sources of new jobs and new technologies."
</P>
<P>
Sharing Tang's view that Hong Kong's return to China will
prompt among Hong Kongers an increasing sense of comfort of being
a part of a modernizing China with a bright future, Raymond
Ch'ien, chairman of Hong Kong's Industry and Technology
Development Council, said that Hong Kong should promote the
high-tech sector for its sustained development in the future.
</P>
<P>
The two-day symposium, named Countdown to 1997: Roadmap to Hong
Kong's Continued Prosperity, was sponsored by Far Eastern Economic
Review, one of the most influential economic periodicals in the
region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
