<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Growth Triangle Progresses Well in Right Direction: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The
Indonesia-Malaysia-Singapore Growth Triangle (IMS-GT) has
progressed well enough to warrant more and more members being
added.
</P>
<P>
The assessment was made by Linda Low from the National
University of Singapore's Business Faculty in her paper "Overall
Reassessment of the IMS-GT Triangle" at the International
Conference on IMS-GT which opened today in Johor Baharu, about 370
kilometers southeast of here, according to the Malaysian national
news agency Bernama.
</P>
<P>
The IMS-GT appears to be progressing in the right direction
while several issues and problems are raised for reflection and
rumination, she said.
</P>
<P>
"Indubitably, the biggest challenge facing the pioneer in
growth triangles is the intense growing competition of similar
configurations within ASEAN like IMT-GT
(Indonesia-Malaysia-Thailand Growth Triangle), BIMP (Brunei,
Indonesia, Malaysia, Philippines) and other projects revolving
around the Mekong River," she observed.
</P>
<P>
She was of the view that the IMS-GT must be consistent and
supportive of wider frameworks of co-operation including ASEAN,
AFTA, APEC and even WTO.
</P>
<P>
She said progress in growth triangles adds incremental value
and confidence to bigger frameworks and they should be tapped as
useful appendages rather than treated as outside these structures.
</P>
<P>
She also said quantity and quality of labor in the IMS-GT as a
competitive attraction needs more attention.
</P>
<P>
Information technology (IT) and networks become an area for
co-operation as skills training and wide application of IT would
be in line with the countries' aspirations as well as investors'
needs, she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
