<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flexible Approach Proposed for Growth Triangle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The
Indonesia-Malaysia-Singapore Growth Triangle (IMS-GT) will have
the best long-term success if local investors develop a flexible
specialization approach.
</P>
<P>
This was suggested by C.P.F. Luhulima, senior fellow of
Indonesia's Center for Strategic and International Studies (CSIS),
at the two-day international conference on IMS-GT which opened
today in Johor Baharu, about 370 kilometers southeast of here,
according to the Malaysian national news agency Bernama.
</P>
<P>
He said as the global economy kept shifting towards flexible
specialization, manufacturing firms must be able to meet the
client's need in order to survive and, to build a stable base for
long-term development within the framework of sustainable
development.
</P>
<P>
Presenting his paper "Profitability and Sustainability:
Reconciling Conflicting Pressures" at the conference, Luhulima
said the pattern of flexible specialization is appearing
world-wide in which companies develop their own specialization in
one step of industrial processes and then work as sub-contractors
to produce a variety of customized products for different clients.
</P>
<P>
He said there are economic benefits from sub-contracting each
stage of the production process to an enterprise which specializes
in that stage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
