<HEADLINE> Black American Detained in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 24 (Xinhua) -- A black American named Joseph
Morris has been detained and put in prison for unlawful
entry into Iran, Iranian judiciary chief revealed here today.
</P>
<P>
The arrest was revealed by Iran's Judiciary Chief Ayatollah
Mohammad Yazdi at a press conference here today.
</P>
<P>
An aide to the Judiciary chief added that "the gentleman, a
black Muslim, was caught in Ahvaz eight months ago. He has been in
detention since then."
</P>
<P>
A well-informed source at the Judiciary who has met Morris told
Xinhua that Morris is suffering from psychological disorder.
</P>
<P>
"He entered Iran through Pakistani border. When he was caught,
he revealed that he had taken part in the Operation Desert Storm
to drive Iraqis out of Kuwait (in the 1991 Gulf War)," he added.
</P>
<P>
His background has made the official worried that perhaps he is
a spy, the source said.
</P>
<P>
Yazdi denied that there were any other U.S. nationals held
in custody in Iranian jails.
</P>
<P>
"As you know, most Americans left Iran after the Islamic
revolution (in 1979)," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the legal disputes between Iran and the U.S., Yazdi said
that Iran was successful in getting the full reparation from the
U.S. for the families of those killed aboard an Iranian passenger
plane shot down by American forces stationed in the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
Some 290 Iranian passengers aboard an Airbus-A300 were killed
after their plane was hit by a missile fired by USS Vincenne, a
U.S. Navy Cruiser, in July 1988.
</P>
<P>
"Americans did not want to accept the responsibility for the
downing of the Iranian plane, but in the end they had to accept the
responsibility," Yazdi said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
