<HEADLINE> Macao-Born Portuguese on "One Country, Two Systems" Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Macao-Born Portuguese (MBP) believe
Hong Kong's experience in implementing the concept of "one
country, two systems" will be of importance to Macao, and they
wish the policy every success here in the territory.
</P>
<P>
Carlos Marreiros, who was head of the Macao Cultural Institute
and plans to stay on in Macao after the handover in 1999, said
Hong Kong's experience will help ensure the success of the policy
to be carried out also in Macao.
</P>
<P>
"I think Macao can learn a lot from the valuable experience in
Hong Kong in turning the concept into reality," the 40-year-old
architect told Xinhua in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
Born in Macao but educated in Lisbon, Marreiros and others
founded a MBP organization called "Root in Macao" last year,
which, he said, shows their confidence in Macao's future beyond
1999.
</P>
<P>
The MBP community, whose population totals about 10,000, showed
its strength for the first time last year when it participated as
a group in the election of the 6th Macao Legislative Assembly.
</P>
<P>
"We sincerely hope that the concept of 'one country, two
systems' will be carried out successfully in Macao," he
said. "That is the fundamental guarantee of the life of us MBP."
</P>
<P>
His views were echoed by another MBP, Antonio J. Dias Azedo, a
solicitor who has also decided to continue to dwell in Macao after
1999.
</P>
<P>
"I am confident that the promise of lifestyle remaining
unchanged after 1999, which is written into the Basic Law of
Macao, will become a fact," he told Xinhua. "I will stay on so
long as I have a job and can live here. Macao is my hometown."
</P>
<P>
"Macao should take vigorous future-oriented measures concerning
its administration and legal structure," said Azedo," so that
Macao residents can keep their current lifestyle in the future."
</P>
<P>
An MBP member at Macao Legislative Assembly, Leonel Alberto
Alves, said the current (political) structure could not meet the
challenges ahead if further efforts were not made.
</P>
<P>
"Although some major work has been done in the past decade
since the signing of the Sino-Portuguese Joint Declaration," he
said, "we must take further reforms in our legal and
administrative structure."
</P>
<P>
Jose Maneiras, former chairman of the Macao Municipal Council,
was optimistic about the future, as the governments of both China
and Portugal have been carrying out promises in the Joint
Declaration faithfully.
</P>
<P>
"I have nothing to worry about Macao's future," he said. "I
will continue to live in this place where I was born, and continue
to serve Macao as a citizen of the city."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
