<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong to Remain international Financial Center: Economist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The historic handover on June
30, 1997, will not affect adversely Hong Kong's status as an
international financial center in the next five or ten years,
according to an economist with Lehman Brothers.
</P>
<P>
On the contrary, Dr. Miron Mushkat, Lehman Brothers' chief
economist for Asia-pacific Region, said here today that Hong
Kong's return to China will prove beneficial for the Hong Kong
economy in the short term.
</P>
<P>
In a panel discussion on Hong Kong's future in an investor's
perspective, the Warsaw-born economist said: "Hong Kong's economy
is moving smoothly. Looking forward, we believe the growing
momentum will sustain."
</P>
<P>
At one-week countdown to July 1, 1997, when China resumes the
exercise of its sovereignty over Hong Kong, the chief economist
expected greater economic integration between Hong Kong and the
inland areas in the flow of capital and labor. A well-performed
Chinese economy plus the growing integration will produce an
incentive to Hong Kong's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Hong Kong is becoming the center of a
larger region, which covers Macao, and the coastal special
economic zones in southern China, including Zhuhai and Shenzhen.
"With the growing economies of scale, we expect greater efficiency
and greater economic strength. This is the feature of Hong Kong's
economic environment in the next a few years," said Dr. Mushkat.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Hong Kong's status as an international
financial center will be preserved in the medium term.
</P>
<P>
"In an economic perspective, the more China opens up, the more
China reforms, the more China decentralizes, the more China needs
a middleman like Hong Kong, which serves as a bridge between China
and the rest of the world," said Dr. Mushkat, now a Hong Kong
permanent resident, who has been living in this Asian city for 18
years.
</P>
<P>
In the provision of intermediary services, he noted that Hong
Kong continues to enjoy a comparative advantage in economies of
scale, supporting industries of international trade, a
cosmopolitan outlook and a biculatural and bilingual character.
"Shanghai will have no realistic challenge to Hong Kong in the
medium term," he added.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Mushkat said that to maintain its status as an
international financial center, Hong Kong needs to maintain its
present legal system, keep an effective and neutral civil service,
ensure a free flow of information, keep corruption at bay, and
maintain a free and market-driven economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
