<HEADLINE> Reduced Habitat Forces Tigers to Maul People: Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- An expert of the Worldwide Fund
for Nature has blamed the decreasing size of the Sumatran tiger's
habitat for the attacks that killed three people in Indonesia's
West Lampung province recently.
</P>
<P>
"The dwindling size of their natural habitat has caused the
Sumatran tigers to go on a rampage," expert on tigers Ron Lilley
said here today.
</P>
<P>
The Natural Resources Conservation Center in Lampung said
Monday it is trying to catch a Sumatran tiger that has killed
three people and injured three others in Sumerjaya subdistrict
between June 7 and 20.
</P>
<P>
Lilley said people have converted the tiger's habitat into
plantations or settlement areas, prompting the animal to retaliate
by attacking people.
</P>
<P>
Lilley, who is also head for conservation of animal species,
thus called for integrated planning on the use of the country's
natural resources.
</P>
<P>
He also urged local administrations to preserve the natural
habitat of wild animals and provide a buffer zone for them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
