<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 12:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Court to Try German Companies Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Iran announced today that it will
soon start the trial of German companies which offered chemical
weapons to Iraq during the Iran-Iraq war in 1980s.
</P>
<P>
The judiciary Chief Ayatollah Mohammad Yazdi said at a press
conference that a Iranian court has completed investigation
into German involvement in the Iraqi chemical attacks against
Iran.
</P>
<P>
Yazdi said, it is till undecided whether it will be an open
trial. However, he declined to name the German companies, saying
that Iran has been told by German authorities that some of the
companies involved have already been put on trial in Germany.
</P>
<P>
"They have told us that they have prosecuted these
companies. Naturally the trials held in Germany cannot answer our
questions," he added.
</P>
<P>
Yazdi held top German officials responsible for the shipment of
chemical weapons to Iraq
</P>
<P>
"The export of chemical materials could not have been
without the permission of government officials," he added.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the trial would take a long time because
there were different companies that were involved.
</P>
<P>
In April, a German court found Iranian leaders responsible for
the killing of four Kurdish dissidents in a restaurant in Berlin
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Iran retaliated by preparing a lawsuit against 24 German
companies responsible for supplying Iraq with the chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
On April 7, the judicial authorities demanded 24 German firms and a
number of German government officials to appear in an Iranian court
on charges for chemical weapon supply to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
However, the Iranian authorities did not published the names
of the 24 German companies nor names of German government officials
involved in the chemical supply deal.
</P>
<P>
Last December, Iran accused 84 German companies, including
Toysen, Zigma and Hebergerbau, of supplying chemical weapons to
Iraq during the war.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah Mazandarani, Secretary General of the Association for
Helping Victims of Iraq's Chemical Warfare, said that Iran has
collected a considerable volume of information regarding Germany
in connection with chemical weapon supplies to Iraq during the
eight-year war.
</P>
<P>
He said that some 25,000 Iranians were killed and 65,000 others
were injured in the war with Iraq as victims of chemical bombs.
</P>
<P>
"In addition to German firms there were some 18 U.S. and
British firms that were supplying (chemical weapons to) the
Iraqis," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that most of the chemicals were given to Baghdad under
the cover of providing pesticide to the Iraqis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0125 </DOCNO>
