<HEADLINE> Johnson Waits for IAAF Call on Wildcard Invite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Double Olympic champion Michael
Johnson said here on Tuesday that he was still waiting to hear
from the IAAF about a possible wild card entry for the world
championships in Athens in August.
</P>
<P>
Johnson, unable to run in the American trials because of a
strained quadricep muscle suffered in his 150 meters duel with
Canadian 100 meters world record holder Donovan Bailey, said it
was up to the 'highly paid IAAF executives' whether he received an
invitation or not.
</P>
<P>
"I am just focussing on my race in Paris on Wednesday. If they
decided to ring me and ask me as a wildcard entry then I would
consider it," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, France's Marie-Jose Perec, who also claimed double
Olympic gold last year, said it was not a good idea to award wild
card entries.
</P>
<P>
"If you do that then you might as well forget national
championships. It's not fair that people like Michael Johnson and
Gail Devers can walk in to a championship event while others have
to go through the normal process of qualifiying," the Frenchwoman
said.
</P>
<P>
An IAAF official said they had received plenty of queries over
the situation and that it would be discussed. 
</P>
