<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Seeks Inflows of Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's four states, part
of the Indonesia-Malaysia-Singapore Growth Triangle (IMS-GT), are
actively seeking inflows of foreign investment for high-technology
operations.
</P>
<P>
The four states -- Johor, Melaka (Malacca), Negeri Sembilan and
Pahang -- would make the southern peninsular a highly attractive
region for inward investments, Johor chief minister Abdul Ghani
Othman said when opening the "International Conference on IMS-GT:
Borderless Area for Sustainable Progress" in Johor Baharu, about
370 kilometers southeast of here, today.
</P>
<P>
"We focus on the quality of investments rather than the
quantity with a shift towards more capital and
technology-intensive activities," he was quoted by the Malaysian
national news agency Bernama as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said entrepreneurs from the four states were also encouraged
to undertake reverse investment in surrounding countries,
especially in the growth triangle.
</P>
<P>
The IMS-GT has the potential to develop as a critically
important international trade center since it is strategically
located along one of the world's busiest shipping routes and at
the heart of a resource rich and dynamic region, he said.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the four states in Malaysia, the IMS-GT covers
Singapore and the provinces of Riau, West Sumatera, Jambi,
Bengkulu, South Sumatera, Lampung and West Kalimantan in
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The IMS-GT's geographical area is 565,000 square kilometers
with a market size of 34 million people.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's investments in Indonesia and Singapore exceed 2.1
billion ringgit (about 840 million U.S. dollars). In 1996,
Singapore alone was estimated to invest 4.8 billion ringgit (about
1.92 billion U.S. dollars) in manufacturing projects in Malaysia,
the bulk of it in the IMS-GT.
</P>
<P>
The IMS-GT provides a framework for bilateral and trilateral
cooperation in various sectors that include manufacturing,
agriculture, forestry, tourism, shipping and communications.
</P>
<P>
The two-day conference aims to bring together key government
officials and private sector delegates to discuss the future
direction of the growth triangle and to obtain input on how
cooperation can be enhanced, Bernama said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
