<HEADLINE> hkhk - British Grandmother Arrives in HK on Round-the-World Helicopter Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 24 (Xinhua) -- A 56-year-old grandmother
arrived here on Tuesday on a round-the-world helicopter flight to
raise money for a Hong Kong-based charity organization.
</P>
<P>
Since their departure from Denham of Britain on May 10 this
year, Jennifer Murray and co-pilot Quentin Smith have been
traveling for 46 out of the 97 days planned for their super-long
trip, "almost non-stop" as Murray described.
</P>
<P>
Upon arriving in Hong Kong, they have covered nearly half of
their total distance of 24,000 miles (38,400 kilometers) and are
about one third of the way around the world, after visiting 20 out
of the 30 countries and regions on their schedule.
</P>
<P>
The red G-Murray light helicopter is the first and last
civilian British helicopter to fly into Hong Kong and will be here
during the historic handover, thus making it the first civilian
British helicopter to fly out of Hong Kong after it becomes a
special administrative region of China at midnight on June 30.
</P>
<P>
Housewife, mother and grandmother, Murray has been flying since
learning it in 1994 and she has now over 600 hours of flying
experience.
</P>
<P>
Jennifer got married in 1966 to Simon Murray, who is Executive
Chairman Asia Pacific for Deutsche Bank Group. Having spent their
last 30 years in Hong Kong, they have three children and two grand
children.
</P>
<P>
The 33-year-old Smith, a former freestyle helicopter flying
world champion, is an instructor of his father helicopter company
HeliAir, the largest private helicopter training company in
Britain.
</P>
<P>
From the expedition, Save the Children Fund (Hong Kong) has so
far received donations of 447,985 HK dollars (57,433 U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Although they have avoided such bad weather conditions as
storms, cyclones and monsoon rains, the worst to date took place
during their flight across the British Channel, Murray said at a
post-landing press conference here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We were really lucky so far on the trip," she smiled.
</P>
<P>
After a stop over here to witness Hong Kong's handover just a
week away, the pair will leave on July 2 for their next stop in
Japan. They are scheduled to return to Denham on August 15 this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
