<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Slightly Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar ended today
slightly higher, but the market remains tentative ahead of next
week's Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA) board meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed in Sydney at 75.21 U.S. cents, up
from 75.11 at yesterday's close.
</P>
<P>
"With official rates now at parity, any sign that U.S. and
Australian rates may cross over can only intensify negative market
sentiment about the Australian dollar," Commonwealth Bank of
Australia said in its June quarter Economic Outlook publication.
</P>
<P>
But Citibank Ltd. economists Stephen Koukoulas and Annette
Beacher said in a commentary that the Australian dollar currently
looks cheap in a short- to medium-term perspective at levels
approaching 75 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
On the cross rates, the Australian dollar ended weaker.
</P>
<P>
It was at 85.97 Japanese yen from 86.72 and at 1.2935 Deutsche
marks from 1.2996 previously.  
</P>
