<HEADLINE> World Bank to Offer Loans to Kenya's Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has approved 6.9
billion Shillings (about 125 million U.S. Dollars) of credit to
develop Kenya's power industry which is a bottleneck in the
country's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Harold Wackman, the bank's Country Director for Kenya and
Djibouti, said Monday the funding is expected to benefit several
power projects immensely across the eastern African country in
the next two years.
</P>
<P>
The Mombasa-based Kepevu and the OI Karia power project at the
Rift Valley are among the projects to benefit from the funding,
according to local industrial sources.
</P>
<P>
The credit was approved at the just concluded World Bank Board
of Directors meeting held in Washington, said Wackman.
</P>
<P>
He gave no more details but promised to issue a comprehensive
statement this week.
</P>
<P>
The power production was singled out by Kenya's official 1997
Economic Survey as a major impediment slowing down economic
growth. 
</P>
