<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3rd Series of HK's Return to China Commemorative Coins to Be Issued </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The third series of "Hong Kong's
Return to China Gold &AMP; Silver Coins" are expected to be issued in
Hong Kong next week to celebrate the Hong Kong's return to her
motherland.
</P>
<P>
According to a news briefing held here this afternoon by China
Great Wall Coins Investments Ltd., three types of coins from the
third series of gold &AMP; silver commemorative coins will be on sale
overseas, including a 5 oz gold coin, a 0.5 oz gold coin and a 1
oz silver coin.
</P>
<P>
The pictures on the obverse side of all the coins are the same,
showing Tian An Men, ornamental columns, peony flower and the date
of issue with the words "The People's Republic of China".
</P>
<P>
The reverse sides will depict two different designs. the
picture on the 5 oz gold coin will have a portrait of Deng
Xiaoping, surrounded by rays of light in the upper half, the lower
half will show the harbor view of Hong Kong, around the edge there
are the words "the founding of Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region, P.R. China" in Chinese and English.
</P>
<P>
The upper half of reverse sides on the 0.5 oz gold coin and 1
oz silver coin shows the flag of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR), the lower half shows a harbor view
of Hong Kong showing the Convention and Exhibition Center, and in
the center there are fireworks. Around the edge there are the
words "the founding of HKSAR, P.R. China" in Chinese and English.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the China Great Wall Coins Investments Ltd.,
the design of these pictures expresses the "One Country, Two
Systems" principle and symbolizes the future prosperity and
stability of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
He said that each commemorative coin is legal tender of the
People's Republic of China, and is accompanied by a Certificate
Authenticity, signed by the Governor of the People's Bank of
China.
</P>
<P>
The entire collection of commemorative coins contains three
series. There has been tremendous market response since the first
and second series were issued on December 1, 1995 and July 1, 1996
respectively, the spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
