<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Manila's Traffic Nightmare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- If you ask a visitor about his
unpleasant impression of the Philippine capital of Manila, his
most likely answer would be the city's traffic congestion.
</P>
<P>
Indeed, traffic congestion is perhaps the most magnified
problem of Manila and no resident in the city can be free from the
traffic nightmare.
</P>
<P>
Because of traffic jams, most Manila residents have to spend as
much as two hours each way to go to work on weekdays.
</P>
<P>
Because of traffic jams, any gatherings or functions in the
city, regardless of their importance, would always start one or
two hours behind schedule.
</P>
<P>
Because of traffic jams, the authorities even take the opening
day of school as an important national event and deploy several
thousand more policemen and their assistants on the road to ease
the traffic.
</P>
<P>
Manila's traffic nightmare is not as chilly as Bangkok's.
However, the problem is worsening day by day with increases of new
private cars and migrants from the countryside.
</P>
<P>
In Manila, with 1.6 million vehicles on the road, travel for a
short distance by car sometimes takes more time than by foot.
During the rush hour, the travel speed of a car is often reduced
to less than 10 kilometers a hour. At some road intersections, one
often waits for half an hour or over 40 minutes to pass.
</P>
<P>
On roadsides of Manila's major streets, crowds of commuters
often wait anxiously for hours under the scorching sun for
jeepneys, a jeep-like car which can each carry about 15
passengers.
</P>
<P>
Abina B., a security guard at Manila's Gotesco Tower, said: "I
work for 12 hours a day and spend more than five hours on travel
from here to my home, and from my home to the tower. I don't have
enough time to sleep after doing some housework for my wife."
</P>
<P>
And nobody can escape from the nightmare of heavy congestion,
including the police, who often have to be patient enough to put
up with the traffic moving at a crawl even when they escort
visiting foreign dignitaries. Sometimes, President Fidel Ramos'
convoy could also be blocked by kilometers of cars on the road.
</P>
<P>
For businessmen, time means money. Therefore, some rich
businessmen, such as Lucio Tan, chairman of the Philippine
Airlines, have bought helicopters to fly them from home to office.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the Metro Manila Development Authority has
tried several schemes to ease the traffic, but with little
success. Last year, the authority first adopted an "odd-even
scheme" which bans private vehicles from certain major roads on
alternate days depending on whether license plates end in odd or
even numbers.
</P>
<P>
When no improvement was seen months later, the authority
introduced a "Unified Vehicular Reduction Program" in the whole
city. Under the program, private cars whose plate numbers end in 0
or 1 are banned from roads in the city on Monday, 2 or 3, on
Tuesday... On the weekend, bans on private cars are lifted.
Although the program still remains in force, it has achieved
little in decongesting the increasingly clogged streets.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of this year, the authority opened an
"expressway" on major roads in the city for any cars carrying
fewer than four people. But the experiment lasted less than 10
days amid protests from city residents who charged that it created
more chaos on roads.
</P>
<P>
Who should be blamed for the worsening situation?
</P>
<P>
Some Manila residents blame it on the inability of the Metro
Manila Development Authority to enforce traffic rules.
</P>
<P>
Some others, including traffic authorities, point the finger at
the jeepney drivers who they said lack road discipline.
</P>
<P>
Still others said the effective marketing gimmicks of car
dealers should be responsible for the problem.
</P>
<P>
In fact all of these may have been attributed to the worsening
situation. Driving in Manila is not easy for new comers who
carefully observe traffic regulations. But jeepney drivers stop
anywhere on the road to let passengers get on or off.
</P>
<P>
"Jeepney drivers usually ignore traffic regulations. Their cars
run like snakes and could collide with others any time," said
Toitito Chaluya, a professional driver for a foreign government
organization.
</P>
<P>
"Driving in Manila is like participating in an auto race,
nobody will give you way when you give signals for overtaking or
making a turn, " complained a Japanese journalist.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the main cause of the traffic nightmare is
perhaps not the lacking of road discipline, but the unlimited
purchase of private cars, a shortage of buses and rapid
urbanization.
</P>
<P>
In Manila, the municipal authorities try to reduce the number
of cars on the road by adopting new schemes, but take no steps to
limit the purchase of private cars. As a result, 400 new cars are
added each day to the roads of the city, where there are 1.6
million cars already.
</P>
<P>
To maintain its tradition, Manila keeps jeepneys as its main
transportation means, though a jeepney can only take about 15
passengers, while a bus can carry as many as 80 people and take up
a road space no more than that for two jeepneys.
</P>
<P>
Also, as several hundred people from the countryside flock each
day to Manila, whose population has increased from less than 8
million in the 1980s to 9.5 million now, the city's roads will
become even more crowded in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
Experts have proposed the development of more light rail
transit and the introduction of trams and buses as transportation
means for Manila, but these proposals would take years to be
materialized if the authorities respond favorably. Therefore,
Manila's traffic nightmare will continue, at least for some time.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
