<HEADLINE> Chinese FM Reconfirms Support for Non-Aligned Movement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier and Foreign
Minister Qian Qichen said here today that China, as an observer of
the Non-Aligned Movement, has all always supported the theme and
principle of the Movement.
</P>
<P>
Qian made this statement during a meeting with Colombian
Vice-Foreign Minister Pilar Gaitan De Pombo.
</P>
<P>
He also extended a warm welcome to Colombian President Ernesto
Samper Pizano, who is expected to attend the ceremony celebrating
the return of Hong Kong to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Since the forging of diplomatic ties between China and
Colombia in 1980, bilateral relations have grown steadily, and
their co-operation in politics, culture, science and technology
has been fruitful, Qian said, adding the people of the two countries
have deepened their understanding and friendship.
</P>
<P>
He described President Samper's visit to China last October as
a great success which marks the beginning of a new developmental
era of Sino-Colombian ties.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government attaches importance to relations between
the two countries, and is willing to push bilateral ties of
cooperation to a new high through concerted efforts with the
Colombian government on the basis of mutual respect, equality, and
mutual benefit.
</P>
<P>
Gaitan conveyed Colombian Foreign Minister Mejia Velez's
regards to Qian. She said that Colombia is satisfied with the two
countries' sound co-operation in bilateral and international
issues, adding Colombia hopes to increase co-operation with China
in trade, investment, judiciary, drugs control and other fields.
</P>
<P>
Gaitan reiterated Colombia's support for China's entry to the
World Trade Organization, and its pursuit of the "one China"
policy.
</P>
<P>
Extending her congratulations over Hong Kong's hand-over, she
said Hong Kong's return will be a historic event, and the
Colombian government and people believe in a brighter future of
Hong Kong and China as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Gaitan arrived in Beijing Sunday at the invitation of
Vice-Foreign Minister Li Zhaoxing, and they held discussions on
bilateral relations and other issues of common concern. 
</P>
</TEXT>
