<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hanson's Views Has No Impact On Australia's Ties With Asia: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Australian government
completely rejects the remarks by independent legislator Pauline
Hanson on Asian immigrants and race issues, Foreign Minister
Alexander Downer said today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, Downer said, "The Australian
government obviously completely rejects what Pauline Hanson says
about Asian immigration and race issues."
</P>
<P>
Downer described Pauline Hanson's remarks as "totally offensive"
and advised her to educate herself on the enormous benefits that
Australia has gained from Asian immigration to Australia.
</P>
<P>
"We like her to educate herself about the enormous benefits
Australia gets as well as Asia gets from the economic interaction
between Australia and Asia," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The political relationship we have with Asian partners are very
close, very productive. And Pauline Hanson will do well to learn
something about that as well", the foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
During her maiden speech to Australian parliament last
September, Pauline Hanson made a controversial call for a cut in
intake of Asian immigrants and an end to foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Her remarks, which invoked strong protests from Asian
immigrants in the country and concerns from some Asian countries,
has not produced any impact on Australia's economic relationships
with countries in the region, Downer said.
</P>
<P>
He also predicted a short life for Pauline Hanson's One Nation
party, saying that the party is just like "a comet in the sky and
will soon disappear."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
