<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Gas-Field Flames Subsiding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The gas-ignited fire at the
Magurchhara gas field in northeastern Bangladesh has lost its
intensity and is now reduced to two small flames raging below 10
feet (about three meters), said reports reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, experts from Singapore and America are busy pumping
out the water that has accumulated in the area due to rain and
water flowing from the nearby hillocks and construction work on
the relief well is likely to start soon.
</P>
<P>
The fire, caused by a massive explosion on June 15 during
drilling by the U.S company Occidental, has engulfed the gas field
and scorched nearby trees, houses and rail tracts.
</P>
<P>
Occidental has finalized a two-phase plan to douse the fire and
cap the mouth of the well, said concerned sources.
</P>
<P>
In the first phase, a relief well will be drilled and then a
dynamic "kill" will be employed using high density barite-laden
fluid pumped at high rates.
</P>
<P>
In the second phase, both well bores will be cemented, the land
around the well re-stabilized and the area cleaned of blown-out
subsurface formation.
</P>
<P>
Occidental plans to launch a main operation to extinguish the
fire by next month. But sources said the operation might be
delayed as the main equipment needed for sealing the well is yet
to reach Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
However, there is no sign of any initiative to restore the
road-railway links. The direct railway links in the Sylhet
district with the capital city of Dhaka and the port city of
Chittagong have remained snapped since the fire broke out.
</P>
<P>
An Occidental engineer said he did not feel it too risky for
trains to run through the lines here as the gas pocket had emptied
and there was little chance of further gas blast at the same spot.
</P>
<P>
The railway is incurring an estimated loss of 1.5 million taka
(about 35,000 U.S. dollars) a day due to the fall in passenger and
goods traffic to and from Sylhet, Dhaka and Chittagong.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
