<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Business Community Optimistic about HK's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 24 (Xinhua) -- With only a few days left before
the handover, the foreign business community here is optimistic
about the prospects of Hong Kong after July 1.
</P>
<P>
Latest surveys conducted by the American and Canadian chambers
of commerce in Hong Kong among their member companies show that 95
percent of Hong Kong-based American companies regard the city's
commercial environment over the next five years as either "very
ideal" or "ideal", and 99 percent of the Canadian respondents
expressed the intention of staying in Hong Kong beyond the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
In a recent series of exclusive interviews with the chairmen of
major foreign chambers of commerce in Hong Kong, interviewees told
Xinhua that they believe Hong Kong will maintain its existing
business-friendly environment and achieve long-term stability and
prosperity after July 1.
</P>
<P>
"I am one hundred percent optimistic about Hong Kong's
prospects. I think 98 and even 99 percent of the members of our
chamber hold the same opinion as mine," said Naoya Yokoyama,
chairman of the Hong Kong Japanese Chamber of Commerce and
Industry.
</P>
<P>
Raj Sital, chairman of the Indian Chamber of Commerce in Hong
Kong, said that during the past ten-plus years of Hong Kong's
transitional period, no member of the local Indian business
community has left, because they are firmly convinced in the 'one
country, two systems" principle.
</P>
<P>
Most of these chairmen of foreign chambers of commerce have
been staying in Hong Kong for more than a decade, and have a
fairly good understanding of the local political and economic
systems.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that the success of Hong Kong should be attributed
to a variety of factors, such as the rule of law, low taxes, the
government's policy of non-interference in economic affairs, and
the free port status.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR), which stipulates that the existing social and economic
systems and lifestyle in Hong Kong shall remain unchanged after
the handover, has made sure that all these factors will stay after
July 1, they added.
</P>
<P>
"The American business community is bullish over the
post-handover business climate in Hong Kong," said Douglas Henck,
chairman of the Hong Kong American Chamber of Commerce, the
largest foreign chamber of commerce here with more than 1,100
member companies.
</P>
<P>
Paul S.K. Lam, chairman of the Canadian Chamber of Commerce in
Hong Kong, said that the situation in Hong Kong would remain
stable before and after July 1, and that "the future HKSAR
government will continue to provide easy accesses for business
people from all over the world."
</P>
<P>
"For us, what happens on June 30 is going to be the same as
what happens on July 1, and our business will be done the same
way," Alfred Chown, chairman of the Australian Chamber of
Commerce in Hong Kong, commented on the upcoming handover.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of Hong Kong's future development, most of the foreign
chambers' chairmen shared the view that with the economic backing
of China's interior areas, Hong Kong's current status as an
international financial, trading and shipping center will be
further strengthened, while its economic and trade relations with
various countries and regions will become even closer.
</P>
<P>
"At present, the Asian economy as a whole ranks first in the
world in terms of the economic growth rate. So far as the
geographical location is concerned, Hong Kong is the center of
Asia. So, I think that it will strengthen its status and play an
increasingly important role in the future," Yokoyama, chairman of
the Japanese chamber, noted.
</P>
<P>
Many foreign business people believe that Hong Kong will have a
better investment environment and provide more business
opportunities after July 1.
</P>
<P>
Most business for Indian merchants in Hong Kong involves the
re-export of goods from China's interior areas, Sital said, adding
that the Indian business community is looking forward to Hong
Kong's return to China, for "we believe that our business will
become more successful."
</P>
<P>
Sung Suk Joo, chairman of the Korean Chamber of Commerce in
Hong Kong, described the interior areas of China as "a huge
market."
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong will play an even more important role in promoting
and supporting the modernization drive there," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
