<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Continue Participation in 34 Int'l Organizations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong will continue to
participate in the activities of 34 international organizations
after July 1, announced Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Cui
Tiankai at a routine press conference here today.
</P>
<P>
He said Hong Kong at present has taken part in the activities
of more than 30 inter-governmental international organizations in
one capacity or another.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the relevant provisions of the Sino-British
Joint Declaration and the Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR), HKSAR may continue to take part in
the activities of these international organizations in an
appropriate capacity after July 1, 1997, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Ever since 1985, for the purpose of a smooth transition of Kong
Kong, the Chinese and British sides have engaged in consultations
on relations between Hong Kong and the above-mentioned
international organizations and have agreed on Hong Kong's
continued participation in the activities of 34 inter-governmental
international organizations in the future, he said.
</P>
<P>
After July 1, 1997, HKSAR may, as members of delegations of the
Chinese Government, take part in the activities of 19
inter-governmental international organizations and attend the
relevant conferences thereof, including the International Civil
Aviation Organization and International Monetary Fund, according
to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
HKSAR may also, as a member or a associate member or in other
capacities, using the name of "Kong Kong, China," take part in the
activities of 15 inter-governmental international organizations,
including the Asian Development Bank and International Maritime
Organization, he added.
</P>
<P>
The above-mentioned arrangements are consistent with the
relevant provisions of the Sino-British Joint Declaration and the
Basic Law of the HKSAR as well as the charters of the relevant
international organizations, he said, adding that they are
commensurate with the status of Hong Kong and serve the practical
needs of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
He said the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of China has made
diplomatic moves in this regard by presenting notes to the 34
international organizations in which to make clear the future
relations between HKSAR and these international organizations and
the capacity in which HKSAR may participate in their relevant
activities.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman expressed his belief that HKSAR's continued
participation in these international organizations in an
appropriate capacity is conducive to the smooth transition of Hong
Kong and will forcefully promote the development of the external
economic relations and trade of the HKSAR as well as its long-term
economic prosperity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
