<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- After four people suspected of being involved in a pedophile
cassette producing network committed suicide following a
nationwide police crackdown, Minister of Justice Elisabeth Guigou
questioned the necessity to make the "spectacular arrests" and the
high degree of media exposure about it. But the justice
departments have defended the operation as justified.
</P>
<P>
-- After two days of calm, the Congolese capital Brazzaville
Monday again fell into a symphony of destruction with all heavy
and light weapons raging. Fighting resumed after the "Cobras"
militiamen of former President Denis Sassou-N'Guesso pounded the
parliament building where 125 deputies and 60 senators were
attending a swearing-in ceremony of the Constitutional Council.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The plan announced by Prime Minister Lionel Jospin to let
all people who have worked 40 years to retire with a satisfactory
pension will cost 26.4 billion to 39.5 billion francs (4.5 billion
to 6.8 billion U.S. dollars) to France, which already maintains
the record high percentage of population who stop working at the
age of 55. Moreover, the retirement plan could encourage
enterprises to abuse it to exclude aged workers.
</P>
<P>
-- President Jacques Chirac proposed Monday at the United
Nations second Earth Summit in New York that France host a
conference on saving the planet's water resources at the beginning
of 1998 in Paris. He also appealed to the international community
to launch a 10-year plan to give all the villages of Third World
countries, especially those in Africa, one well that provides
drinkable water. 
</P>
