<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Develops Water-Efficient Irrigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- China will devote great efforts to
spreading water-efficient irrigation to ensure the supply of grain
and cotton.
</P>
<P>
Chen Lei, president of the Chinese National Commission on
Irrigation and Drainage (CNCID), reaffirmed this strategy at a
meeting commemorating the international day of irrigation and
drainage, today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was attended by officials and experts from both
China and the international community, including the United
Nations Development Program.
</P>
<P>
Chen Lei, who also serves as the director of the Rural Water
Resources Department of the Ministry of Water Resources, claimed
that the reason that China can feed 22 percent of the world's
population with just seven percent of the world's farmland is that
China has 22 percent of the world's irrigated farmland.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that China's irrigated farmland had been expanded to
50.67 million ha by the end of 1995, from only 16 million ha
during the post-liberation days. Although less than 40 percent of
the country's farmland is currently irrigated, they turn out 75
percent of the country's grain, 80 percent of cotton, and 90
percent of vegetables.
</P>
<P>
The official said that China plans to have more than 3.33
million ha of farmland equipped with water-efficient irrigation
facilities during the remaining five years of the century.
</P>
<P>
He said that China is willing to strengthen cooperation and
exchanges with other countries in the field of irrigation and will
actively participate in and support the work of the International
Commission on Irrigation and Drainage (ICID).
</P>
<P>
The 47-year-old ICID will elect its new leadership in the
coming September in England. China's Zhang Qishun, who is vice
president of the China Institute of Water Resources and Hydropower
Research and secretary general of the Chinese National Commission
on Irrigation and Drainage, will run for the vice presidency of
the international organization.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Xu Zhifang of China served as a vice president of the
organization in 1991-1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
