<HEADLINE> At Least 20 People Killed by Floods in Chile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, June 23 (Xinhua) -- At least 20 people have been
killed by floods caused by torrential rains in central and
southern Chile since the beginning of June.
</P>
<P>
The floods have also destroyed about 15,000 houses, causing
51,000 people homeless, Interior Minister Carlos Figueroa Serrano
said today after an inter-departmental meeting held to review the
situation.
</P>
<P>
Among the homeless across the country, 8,600 have been settled
down in temporary shelters set up in the relief centers.
</P>
<P>
Medical centers are operating normally throughout the country
and hence there is no breakout of epidemics so far and only the
number of patients with respiratory problems has increased
slightly, he said.
</P>
<P>
The government has declared eight of the country's 13 regions,
including the Metropolitan region of Santiago, disaster-hit areas.
</P>
<P>
Since the start of this month, a vast area ranging from the
Third Region to the Tenth Region have seen heavy rainfalls and
snowfalls three times more than usual, which is known as the El
Nino phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
The floods submerged villages and cities, interrupted highway
transportation and forced the closing down of seaports and
airports.
</P>
<P>
The Education Ministry today ordered schools in the
disaster-hit areas to close for winter vacation ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
The meteorological agency of Chile forecast more rainfalls in
the coming few days in the areas.
</P>
<P>
The government has allocated 1.2 million U.S. dollars as urgent
relief funds and will decide in the week a total sum needed for
relief operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
