<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Traces of Alleged "Bigfoot" Found in Shennongjia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- China's "Bigfoot" researchers have
recently found tracks believed to be left by a legendary creature,
known as Chinese folklore the "Wild Man", in central China's
Shennonjia National Nature Reserve, sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
Wang Fangchen, head of the non-governmental Committee for
Research on Strange and Rare Creatures, said that a team found
hundreds of very big footprints at a mountainous place 2,600
meters above the sea level in northwest Shennonjia on May 24 this
year.
</P>
<P>
"We have made preliminary conclusions that they were left by
two animals walking on two legs. The biggest footprint is 37 cm
long, very similar to that of a man but is quite larger than
man's, and is different from the footprints of a bear or any other
identified animals," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
He added that these footprints were very clear to identify, and
were believed to be left by a creature weighing some 200 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
Wang's team also found similar footprints left by another two
mysterious creatures in Shennongjia last winter.
</P>
<P>
Shennongjia is a 3,253-square-kilometer mountain area covered
by primitive forests in central China's Hubei Province, north of
the Three Gorges. For 3,000 years, Chinese legends have told of a
mysterious, humanlike creature who is said to roam in its valleys.
</P>
<P>
Most of the witnesses have similar descriptions of the
creature, portraying it as a two-meter-tall animal, with apelike
facial features and a body covered by red hair. It has no tail and
usually leaves large footprints on snow and in the fields.
</P>
<P>
Some scientists believe that "distant relatives" of the "Wild
Man" may include the scary, hairy, Himalayan "Yeti" or "Abominable
Snowman", the oversized-track-leaving "Bigfoot" of northern
California, or the often "glimpsed" but seldom seen "Sasquatch"
who roam the forests of British Columbia, Canada.
</P>
<P>
Some scientists said that the creature may be an unknown
primate, while others argue that what the people have seen may
actually be bears or monkeys.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that the uncovering of the myth will be of great
scientific significance. But the researchers should avoid making
quick conclusions unless hard scientific evidence is obtained, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Wang used to be the head of a failed high-profile expedition to
search for the "Wild Man" in Shennongjia in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Photo Exhibition on Hong Kong Opens in Jakarta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- A week-long photo exhibition on
the history and development of Hong Kong opened here today to
celebrate the historic event of Hong Kong's return to China on
July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The opening ceremony, which was attended by more than 500
people of various circles, was presided over by Indonesia's
Information Minister Hartono.
</P>
<P>
In their speeches at the ceremony, President of the Association
of Indonesia-China Economic, Social and Cultural Cooperation
Sukamdani S. Gitosardjono and Chinese Ambassador to Indonesia Zhou
Gang spoke of the significance of Hong Kong's return to China.
</P>
<P>
Sukamdani said that with the return of Hong Kong to China, the
opportunity for the Indonesian business community to promote its
economic relations with its Chinese counterparts will certainly
become bigger. Moreover, from July 1, 1997, the existing economic
system will exist under the "one country, two systems" concept, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Zhou said the resumption of China's exercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong is a great event in the modern history
of China and the world and marks a major step forward made by the
Chinese people toward their lofty goal of the reunification of the
motherland.
</P>
<P>
On display are some 210 large photographs depicting various
activities, events, places, scenery and historical legacies of
Hong Kong from the Qing Dynasty to the present time.
</P>
<P>
The photo exhibition is jointly organized by the Association of
Indonesia-China Economic, Social and Cultural Cooperation and the
Chinese Embassy here.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
