<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Peace Benefits Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The peace now prevailing in
neighboring Mozambique has benefited Zambia with increased import
and export cargo through the port of Beira of the once war-torn
country.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent Beira Corridor Group publication,
Zambia's exports over the 1995 to 1996 increased from 25,000 tons
to 43,500 tons while its imports rose from 26,100 tons to 35,500
tons during the same period.
</P>
<P>
Zambia uses the Beira route to mainly export its copper,
according to the newsletter.
</P>
<P>
The trade route is one of the cheapest used by Zambia to reach
its Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
Another trade route of similar importance to its overseas
market likely to be revamped is the Bengwela railway through
Angola.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan Government has said it is working towards
rehabilitating the landmine infested line for both passenger and
goods transport. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
