<HEADLINE> Kenya, India to Tackle Trade Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Business representatives from
Kenya and India have resolved to initiate joint efforts in the
next two years to narrow trade deficit between the two countries,
the Daily Nation newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Devender Singh, the leader of an Indian delegation, said the
trade imbalance between the two countries is on the rise.
</P>
<P>
Although Kenya's exports to India have increased by 17
percent, imports from the Asian country have dropped by 30
percent.
</P>
<P>
"The existing trade imbalance between the two still favors
India," said Singh.
</P>
<P>
However, he failed to reveal the sum of the trade deficit and
other details on bilateral trade. 
</P>
