<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Aims to Be World's Next Largest Trading Entity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) will possibly become one of the world's three
largest trading entities by 2020, following the North American
Free Trade Area and the European Union.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine News Agency today quoted a paper on ASEAN vision
2020 as saying that ASEAN, with an area of 4.5 million square
kilometers, may develop into a most attractive area with a
combined gross domestic product of 2 trillion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Both Brunei and Singapore would be among the richest countries
in the world. Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines and Thailand
would become full-blown developed countries while Cambodia, Laos
and Myanmar, to be admitted to ASEAN next month, as well as
Vietnam would achieve newly developed country status, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
The worst case scenario, however, is that intra-ASEAN trade
still comprises less than 30 percent of the group's total trade,
the paper said, adding that new forms of non-tariff barriers and
anti-dumping measures would limit the free trade movement of
products and the development of services within the region.
</P>
<P>
If so, the ASEAN region would be only earning less than 1
trillion dollars by the year 2020, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
To realize the higher end, ASEAN member countries are firming
up ways including the eradication of poverty and the growth of
economic triangles in the region.
</P>
<P>
The paper said ASEAN has set 2020 as its target date for the
eradication of poverty. Its Chamber of Commerce and Industry is
also coming up with a paper on how ASEAN member countries can
concretely address the issue of poverty.
</P>
<P>
During the meetings in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, in July, ASEAN
will also outline ways for how to enhance the growth of economic
triangles in the region, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, ASEAN is also targeting closer economic
integration by 2010, closer cohesiveness with regards to economic
policy and elimination of barriers for a freer flow of capital
within the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
