<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Constructs Stele Garden for Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- China plans to carve names of
20,000 newspapers and periodicals on stone tablets.
</P>
<P>
The orchard of steles, located in Xianning City, central
China's Hubei province, will cover about 6.6 ha..
</P>
<P>
Xu Kongzhang, a newspaperman in his sixties, initiated the
project in the province. "Ancient Chinese newspapers are to be
included in the artificial forest, which aims to highlight a
history of more than 1,000 years of China's newspaper and
periodical production." said he.
</P>
<P>
The tablet forest is designed as a big garden, in which
flowers, trees and ancient Chinese buildings will be planted or
constructed as decorations.
</P>
<P>
Four million yuan have been raised, said Xu, adding the
total cost is estimated at about 100 million yuan,
</P>
<P>
The garden construction will be completed in three phases. The
1,000 most influential newspapers and magazines in the country will
be carved in the first phase.
</P>
<P>
The artificial forest is scheduled to be finished in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Eighteen tablets have been finished in the garden, including
one for "Speaking Truth", a periodical marked with the autograph
of the late Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping. Each tablet stands two
meters tall and 1.2 meter wide, and weighs more than one ton.
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily", China's leading national newspaper, with an
autograph by late chairman Mao Zedong has also been inscribed.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Achieves Bumper Rice Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam harvested more than 13.2
million tons of rice for the winter-spring crop this year, up by
1.039 million tons from that of last year, local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Of the increase, northern provinces accounted for 230,000 tons
and southern provinces 806,000 tons, the General Department of
Statistics was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The rice-growing areas rose 4.6 percent to some 2.676 million
hectares in the country from that of last season.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to good weather and new high-yield rice strains, the
average yield was estimated at 4.95 tons per hectare, 0.19 tons
higher than the previous crop.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the rice output, 1.3 million tons of other
grains were harvested in the season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
