<HEADLINE> Hani Killers' Amnesty Case Postponed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, JUNE 24 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Truth and
Reconciliation Commission (TRC) has postoned to August 11 the
amnesty hearing of two men convicted of the assassination of
South African Communist Party (SACP) leader Chris Hani.
</P>
<P>
TRC's amnesty committee made the decision because that
supporting documentation for the convicted Clive Derby-Lewis and
Janusz Walus's applications were incomplete, and Hani's widow,
Limpho Hani would be unable to attend the full proceedings as she
was due to leave for the United States for an official visit
today.
</P>
<P>
It took about 10 minutes to make the decision after hearing
legal arguments for and against the postponement, requested by
lawyers for the Hani family and the SACP, local daily the Citizen
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The application was opposed by lawyers for the two convicted.
</P>
<P>
Both Derby-Lewis and Walus were sentenced to death for the
April 1993 slaying of Hani outside his home, but the sentences
were later commuted to life imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
In their written amnesty applications to the TRC, Derby-Lewis
and Walus claimed that they acted alone when they assassinated
Hani.
</P>
<P>
However, the ruling African National Congress and the SACP
believed that Walus and Derby-Lewis had been involved in a
broader conspiracy to kill Hani and was trying to find evidence
to support this theory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
