<HEADLINE> South China Province Getting Balance of Revenue and Expenditure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 24 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong Province
collected more than 19 billion yuan in taxes during the first five
months of this year while spending nearly 18 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The five-month tax collection climbed nearly 26 percent over
the same period in 1996, and the expenditure went up more than 18
percent.
</P>
<P>
The increase is the result of growth of the local stamp duty,
business taxes from finance, insurance, and credit cooperative
sources, and individual income taxes.
</P>
<P>
The province strengthened anti-smuggling efforts and the
management of over-head expenses, helping to increase receipts
from fines and administrative fees.
</P>
<P>
Expenditures flowed mostly into local basic construction and
administrative undertakings, including education and public
security. 
</P>
