<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Farmers Growing Vegetables for Foreign Market (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIANYUNGANG, June 24 (Xinhua) -- "Eyeing foreign vegetable
markets and growing vegetables well" -- this is a motto often
repeated by vegetables growers in Fengxian County of
East China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
Qi Dianhua, a local vegetable grower, said that they used to
grow vegetables only for themselves or traded them at a local
market to exchange for some edible oil and salt.
</P>
<P>
"Nowadays we grow vegetables and sell them for overseas
market," said Qi, "vegetable growing has become a major source of
income for many of us."
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, the current vegetable growing area
makes up one tenth of the county's total arable land. They not
only grow traditional varieties such as Chinese cabbages, radish,
but also popular vegetables of Japan, the Republic of Korea,
France, the Netherlands, and the United States, which sell in a
dozen countries in Asia, Europe and America.
</P>
<P>
A county official in charge of agricultural affairs called it a
historic leap for farmers to change from simple self-reliance to
challenging the international market.
</P>
<P>
"This indicates that Chinese farmers have not only become
adapted to the market economy, but also started to take aim at the
international market," said the official.
</P>
<P>
Vegetables grown by Chinese farmers are brought to the overseas
market mainly by foreign trade departments and companies
authorized to handle foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
Ruyi Company Group, a company specialized in vegetable exports
from Lianyungang, an open port city of east China's Jiangsu
Province, has helped local farmers sell their vegetables to
foreign countries over the past years.
</P>
<P>
The company group has so far built export vegetable growing
bases in 16 provinces, with the total area amounting to 16,667
hectares, where about one million farmers, under the guidance of
the company group, are growing quality vegetables needed by the
overseas market.
</P>
<P>
An executive told reporters that they are responsible for
providing farmers with improved varieties and growing techniques,
and are also responsible for purchase, processing, and export of
vegetables.
</P>
<P>
The company group exported 30,000 tons of vegetables and earned
20 million U.S. dollars from exports in 1996, according to the
executive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Farmers Growing Vegetables for Foreign Market (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Wang Yaxu, head of the Department of Agriculture and Industry
of Lianyungang City, explained that farmers now can earn 7,500
yuan to 12,000 yuan from a hectare of grain grown, but if they
grow vegetables, they can earn 15,000 yuan to 30,000 yuan per
hectare.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey conducted by Wang's department shows that grain
which used to dominate local farmers' income is being replaced by
sideline production.
</P>
<P>
Farmers of Shahe Township, Ganyu County, plant Japanese
radishes in between wheat and maize, a season during which the
land used to lie idle. Their earnings from radish growing are
equivalent to money earned from wheat and maize put together. This
has made it possible for local farmers to double their annual
income without causing a drop in their total grain output.
</P>
<P>
Over the past years, many farmers have built new
multiple-storyed flats with money earned from vegetable growing,
and they proudly call these flats "vegetable root villas".
</P>
<P>
Guo Jiashan, director of the Agricultural Bureau of Lianyungang
City, said farmers have shown great zeal toward vegetable growing
because of better profits.
</P>
<P>
Many areas have also made efforts to foster major
export-oriented enterprises, especially big companies engaged in
export of farm produce and sideline products.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises like Ruyi Company Group now total 1,700 in
Lianyungang, which have provided farmers with good service in
vegetable growing, and taught them agro-techniques, creating
favorable conditions for the county to vigorously expand vegetable
growing.
</P>
<P>
Wang Luolin, deputy president of the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences, said that China has been practicing socialist market
economy, and without bringing farmers into the market, the market
economy could not be counted as a real one.
</P>
<P>
"With the help of leading local enterprises, millions of
farmers have been organized to march towards the market and
eventually become market aware through vegetable growing, and much
labor has gone into the international market by way of processing
high value-added foodstuffs," said Wang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
