<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern African States Fine-Tune EU Position </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Representatives of the
12-nation Southern African Development Community (SADC) began a
two-day internal meeting Monday to fine-tune their position in
future talks with the European Union (EU), a local daily The
Citizen reported today.
</P>
<P>
SADC Executive Secretary Kaire Mbuende was quoted as saying in
Gaborone, capital of Botswana that participants at the meeting
should put forward some trade policy recommendations in order to
succeed the Lome Convention, which expires by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The Lome Convention gives African, Caribbean and Pacific (ACP)
countries wider access to EU markets.
</P>
<P>
Mbuende also suggested that trade experts from the SADC should
focus their EU trade efforts on issues relating to agriculture,
commerce and industry.
</P>
<P>
Following the two-day's meeting, participants are expected to
report back to their respective trade ministers prior to SADC's
annual summit, scheduled to be held in Blantyre, capital of
Malawi in September, said the report.
</P>
<P>
At SADC's last summit in Maseru, capital of Lesotho, member
states agreed to develop a southern African free trade zone
within a decade.
</P>
<P>
The SADC comprises Angola, Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi, Mauritius,
Mozambique, Namibia, South Africa, Swaziland, Tanzania, Zambia and
Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
