<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Has Bright Future: Australian FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Australian Foreign Minister
Alexander Downer expressed the belief here today that Hong Kong
will have a bright and successful future after it returns to China
on July 1 after 156 years of British colonial rule.
</P>
<P>
"I think Hong Kong has a bright future. I think it has a
successful future," the minister said in an interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"We understand the historic importance" of Hong Kong returning
to China, said Downer, who has announced that he will attend the
inauguration ceremonies of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region.
</P>
<P>
"I'm advised that the majority of people in Hong Kong welcome
that development (Hong Kong's return to China). You can see that
from the performances of various markets in Hong Kong. The
financial market has been performing very strongly in recent
times," he noted.
</P>
<P>
That is "a vote of confidence" in the handover, the minister
declared.
</P>
<P>
He said China and Britain signed a joint declaration on the
transition of Hong Kong in 1984 and China has formulated a Basic
Law for Hong Kong, giving the firm commitment that the present
system in Hong Kong will remain in place for 50 years.
</P>
<P>
He believes that Hong Kong will remain as one of the world's
great financial centers, adding that "Hong Kong breeds on the back
of China" and "succeeds because of the vast Chinese market,
particularly in southern China."
</P>
<P>
"I suppose one should add that as long as South China continues
to grow at the present rate of growth -- Guangdong Province is
growing at 20 percent per annum -- then Hong Kong is going to do
very well out of that," he explained.
</P>
<P>
Downer said Australia has a very big interest in Hong Kong,
which he described as one of the country's biggest export markets
and a very important trading partner.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, Hong Kong was Australia's sixth largest destination
for overseas investment and 10th largest trading partner,
accounting for 2.6 percent of Australia's total trade, while
Australia was Hong Kong's 14th largest trading partner, according
to a book published last month by an Australian parliament
committee.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of Australia's planned participation in the handover
ceremonies, Prime Minister John Howard said earlier this month
that his country will do all it can to help ensure a smooth and
successful handover of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"I am very much looking forward to my participation (in the
handover ceremonies)," Downer said.
</P>
<P>
Asked about Australia's policy toward Hong Kong and China's
inland areas after the handover, Downer said, "Certainly there
will be no changes."
</P>
<P>
"Obviously in the case of Hong Kong after the changeover we
recognize that Beijing will be responsible for foreign affairs and
defense matters. As a consequence, the consular agreement that we
have for our representation has been negotiated with Beijing.
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen and I signed an agreement in New York
last year for the consular arrangements."
</P>
<P>
"That is one difference that at foreign policy and defense
level we've been dealing through Beijing. But otherwise I don't
see real changes in substance in the way we'll do with Hong Kong,"
said the minister.
</P>
<P>
"Our relationship with Hong Kong is essentially a commercial
relationship," he said. "We don't have problem with Hong Kong in
terms of trade obstacles, tariff barriers, or very few in terms of
non-tariff barriers as well."
</P>
<P>
"So I will imagine our relationship at the economic level with
Hong Kong will continue just as it has in the last few years,"
Downer said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
