<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy's Cultural Relics Endangered by Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The Colosseum in Rome, the Leaning
Tower in Pisa and other cultural relics across the country will
hardly escape the fate of eventual destruction unless necessary
measures are taken to stop pollution, soil and rain erosion.
</P>
<P>
A report released today by the country's Central Institute of
Restoration said that of the 57,000 cultural relics scattered in
more than 8,000 Italian cities and towns, most are endangered by
serious pollution and erosion.
</P>
<P>
The institute has spent 28 billion lira (about 16 million
U.S. dollars) to conduct a thorough survey on the conditions of
these cultural treasures, thanks to a law passed in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Findings are worrying as it is far from optimistic for the
relics to survive earthquakes, landslides, floods and erosion, the
worsening surrounding environment and poor conditions of
anti-theft systems.
</P>
<P>
Those in the capital suffer the most, the report said.
</P>
<P>
However, the Italian government has decided to take action.
</P>
<P>
Italian Deputy Prime Minister and Culture Minister Walter
Veltroni vowed today to work out a detailed plan of restoration on
the basis of the findings of the survey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
