<HEADLINE> Contract Inked for Power Generators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- A contract was signed in Beijing
Monday to arrange the supply of generating equipment for the third
phase of the Jiangxi Jiujiang Power Plant project, according to
today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
The Chinese signatories of the contract were Jiangxi Jiujiang
Phase III Power Generating Co Ltd (JJPPG) and China National
Technical Import and Export Corp (CNTIC). The foreign parties were
Foster Wheeler Energy Corp, Hitachi Co Ltd and Itochu Corp.
</P>
<P>
According to the contract, JJPPG will purchase two 350
million-watt sub-critical generators from Foster Wheeler Energy
Corp, Hitachi Co Ltd and Itochu Corp.
</P>
<P>
After four years of preliminary negotiations, we hope the
installation of the generating equipment will be finished on
schedule before 2000, said Zha Keming, deputy general manager of
China State Electric Power Corp at the signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Most of the money to purchase the generators is from the 29.6
billion yen (258.56 million US dollars) of the third batch of
Japanese Overseas Economic and Co-operation Fund loans. The loans
should be paid back in 30 years, with an interest rate of 2.3
percent each year.
</P>
<P>
As one of the key power projects during China's Ninth Five-Year
Plan (1996-2000), the third phase of Jiangxi Jiujiang Power Plant
will be able to provide the whole province with 4.9 billion
kilowatt-hours of electricity each year when it is completed. The
project will greatly ease the electric shortage in the region and
promote the development of the local economy, Zha said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
