<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia to Curb Money Laundering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government through the
Bank of Zambia (BOZ) is soon to enact three laws to out law money
laundering activities, pyramid schemes and to safe-guard small
depositors against possible bank failures, the Times of Zambia
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The government decision was disclosed by BOZ assistant
director in the regulatory policy and financial analysis
division, Austin Mwape, at an economic seminar in Kafue, south of
Lusaka, at the last weekend.
</P>
<P>
Mwape said that among the highlights of the proposed
anti-money laundering law is that financial institutions will be
required to know their customers and keep records of transaction.
</P>
<P>
He added that the institutions will not be allowed to keep
anonymous accounts or under fictitious names and the institutions
and their workers would be required to report any knowledge of
suspicion of money laundering.
</P>
<P>
Mwape said that a deposit insurance system will be introduced
to ensure that insured depositors are paid their money in
priority to other creditors in case of bank failure. Deposit
insurance will also help address potential bank failure.
</P>
<P>
On pyramid schemes, Mwape called on the public to report to
the central bank BOZ the existence of any such schemes. He noted
that only a few "early birds" benefit from pyramid schemes while
the rest of the members of such schemes loose their money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
