<HEADLINE> 1,500-year-old Graveyard Found in Scenic Spot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists have
discovered a 1,500 year-old burial ground on Mount Wudang, a
sacred place of Daoism in central China's Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
The graveyard, constructed during the Northern and Southern
dynasties (420-581), lies on the west side of a drilling ground in
the Yuxu Palace, which was used by emperors during the Ming
Dynasty (1368-1644).
</P>
<P>
The grave pit is paved with blue glazed slabs, and porcelain
bowls and pottery wares were found in the tomb passage.
</P>
<P>
A more than 300-year-old drainage system reportedly was also
discovered on the site before this. 
</P>
