<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong-related Data (6): Signing of Sino-British Joint </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 24 (Xinhua) -- After two years of negotiations,
the Chinese and British governments reached an agreement regarding
the future of Hong Kong on September 18, 1984.
</P>
<P>
The two delegations initialed the Joint Declaration on
September 26, 1984.
</P>
<P>
The two governments held the signing ceremony for the
Sino-British Joint Declaration in Beijing on December 19.
</P>
<P>
On may 27, 1985, the two governments exchanged instruments of
ratification in Beijing, whereby the Joint Declaration went into
effect and Hong Kong entered the 12-year transitional period.
</P>
<P>
The Joint Declaration comprises the principal document, Joint
Declaration of the Government of the United Kingdom of Great
Britain and Northern Ireland and the Government of the People's
Republic of China on the Question of Hong Kong, and three Annexes:
"Elaboration by the Government of the People's Republic of China
of its Basic Policies Regarding Hong Kong," "Sino-British Joint
Liaison Group" and "Land Leases."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong-Related Data (7): Basic Contents of Sino- </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Sino-British Joint
Declaration on the Question of Hong Kong contains three parts of
basic contents:
</P>
<P>
First, the Government of the People's Republic of China will
resume the exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong with effect from
July 1, 1997, and the Government of the United Kingdom will
restore Hong Kong to the People's Republic of China on the same
day.
</P>
<P>
Second, the Chinese Government's basic policies regarding Hong
Kong are as follows: A Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR) will be established directly under the authority of the
Central People's Government; the HKSAR will enjoy a high degree of
autonomy, except in foreign and defense affairs which are the
responsibilities of the Central People's Government; the
Government of the HKSAR will be composed of local inhabitants; the
current social and economic systems in Hong Kong will remain
unchanged, and so will the life-style; the laws currently in force
in Hong Kong will remain basically unchanged; the HKSAR will
retain the status of a free port and a separate customs territory,
retain the status of an international financial center, and have
independent finances; using the name of "Hong Kong, China", the
HKSAR may on its own maintain and develop economic and cultural
relations and conclude relevant agreements with states, regions
and relevant international organizations; the maintenance of
public order in the HKSAR will be the responsibility of the
Government of the HKSAR; etc. The above-stated basic policies of
the Chinese Government will remain unchanged for 50 years.
</P>
<P>
Third, relevant principles and concrete stipulations for
cooperation between the People's Republic of China and the United
Kingdom to ensure a smooth handover of power in Hong Kong in 1997.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong-Related Data (8): Birth of Basic Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 24 (Xinhua) -- On April 10, 1985, the Third
Session of the Sixth National People's Congress (NPC) decided to
establish a Drafting Committee for the Basic Law of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (HKSAR).
</P>
<P>
On June 18 the same year, the Sixth NPC Standing Committee
approved the list of members of the Drafting Committee. The
Drafting Committee was composed of 59 noted figures from various
circles and specialists, including 23 from Hong Kong. (By the
ninth meeting of the committee, its membership had decreased to
51, including 18 from Hong Kong. Four members had passed away,
two resigned, and two others been dismissed for conduct that was
incompatible with their capacity.)
</P>
<P>
On July 1, 1985, the Drafting Committee was formally
established and started to work. In the following four years and
eight months, it held nine plenary sessions and 73 panel group
meetings.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, a Consultative Committee for the HKSAR Basic
Law, which consisted of 180 representatives from various circles
in Hong Kong, was set up to serve as a bridge of communication
between Hong Kong residents and the Drafting Committee, as well as
a channel through which the Hong Kong people could express their
opinions and make suggestions.
</P>
<P>
In early 1988, an initial version of the Basic Law (Draft) was
completed and circulated in Hong Kong and the interior area to
extensively solicit opinions for revision. At the end of 1988 and
in early 1989, upon examination by the NPC Standing Committee, the
Basic Law (Draft) was made public in an effort to solicit more
opinions and make further revisions. The Law was adopted by the
NPC and promulgated in April, 1990.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law resulted from the collective wisdom and concerted
efforts of many people in both Hong Kong and the interior area.
Its drafting process is one of full and extensive democratic
consultation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polish Economy on Rapid Growth Track </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The Polish economy has been on a
rapid growth track since the beginning of this year and the speed
thus achieved has been among the highest in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Latest official statistics showed a 7.3 percent rise in the
country's gross domestic product (GDP) in the first five months of
the year, compared to that of the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate, apparently the result of a 9.2 percent
increase in industrial production over the five-month period, came
along with a slower inflation rise and a lower jobless rate.
</P>
<P>
The 4.1 percent inflation over January-May was 0.9 percentage
point down from the same period last year, and the 11.7 percent
unemployment in May was a cut of 0.4 percentage point from April.
</P>
<P>
From 1993 to 1996, the GDP was up 19.5 percent and industrial
output 33.5 percent, while inflation was down from 37 percent to
18.5 percent, and jobless rate from 16.9 percent to 13.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The inflation is expected to stay around 12 percent at the end
of this year.
</P>
<P>
While labeling the economic conditions this year as "better
than expected," the Polish government now is aiming at bringing
down the inflation to within 10 percent and achieving 5-5.7
percent GDP growth next year.
</P>
<P>
Behind the current rapid economic growth in Poland are the
political stability, and the four-year-old left-wing government's
policies for economic recovery and development.
</P>
<P>
Poland took the "shock therapy" eight years ago to overhaul its
economic system, and remarkable achievements have been recorded
ever since.
</P>
<P>
However, the country still faces a number of difficulties,
including its national debt of 198 billion zloty (about 62 billion
U.S. dollars), in which internal debt accounts for 55 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0227 </DOCNO>
