<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. House Votes for More Stealth Bombers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The United States House of
Representatives voted 216-209 today for restarting the B-2
production line to add nine more of the radar-evading stealth
bombers to its force.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft were included in the 268 billion U.S. dollars
defense authorization for the 1998 fiscal year which the House was
to vote for on Tuesday. The total defense funding is 2.6 billion
dollars more than President Bill Clinton requested.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of Defense William Cohen wrote to House National
Security Committee chairman Floyd Spence, objecting the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said the Pentagon was unanimous in its view that "the
cost of further B-2 production cannot be justified."
</P>
<P>
The black, delta-shaped B-2 was originally developed in the
1980s in replacement of the B-1. It uses special "stealth"
radar-evasion technology to penetrate enemy airspace undetected.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon has bought 21 of the planes and the manufacturer
has offered to build another 20. 
</P>
