<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Walled City Tells of Hong Kong History (1) by Xu Xingtang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 24 (Xinhua) -- It is a typical Chinese garden
in the style popular south of the Yangtze and, though smaller than
many of its kind, a famous park on the site of the former Kowloon
Walled City has an extraordinary tale to tell.
</P>
<P>
When a plane hovers over Kowloon to approach Kai Tak Airport,
passengers sitting by portholes can get a glimpse of the small
park right under the line.
</P>
<P>
Although it is called a "city", it does not resemble a city at
all with only an area of only 31,000 sq m. hemmed in by clusters
of grey residential buildings on the Kowloon Peninsular.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is a place to create miracles, as people often
praise, and the Walled City itself is all the more a marvelous
place that no other single locality can match when you recall the
historical burden it had endured over the past 150-plus years.
</P>
<P>
Overlooking the Kowloon Bay, the strategical importance of this
site is obvious. As early as 1668, the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911)
set up a signal post here and, around 1810, a fortress was built
at the beach head for defense purpose.
</P>
<P>
After British intruders seized the Hong Kong Island in 1841,
the place became even more vital to China's maritime defenses. And
from 1843 to 1847, the Chinese garrison troops enclosed the site
with tall stone walls, hence the name "Walled City". Inside the
city, there were scores of structures for military purpose and
residential houses.
</P>
<P>
The heads of the Qing Dynasty defending troops were the
Commodore of the Dapeng Brigade and the Kowloon Assistant Military
Inspectorate, whose official residences were named "Yamen" then,
which still remain intact inside today. When the city walls were
completed, there were some 250 troopers stationed there, which
subsequently increased to some 500 in 1898.
</P>
<P>
Despite fierce resistance by local residents, the British
troops marched further northernward in 1898, and occupied by force
large tracts of land south of the Shumchun river and islands
around the Hong Kong Island, which were subsequently named "New
Territories". Even then the Walled City was still in the hands of
Chinese soldiers, even it was then a secluded area.
</P>
<P>
After their seizure of the Hong Kong Island, the "New
Territories" and the islands scattered in the surrounding waters,
the British rulers felt extremely uneasy with the Walled City --
it was as if a nail pegged in their eyes.
</P>
<P>
And in 1899, the haughty British forces broke into the city and
forced the Qing garrison troops out, turning the city into a
semi-anarchistic squatter slum.
</P>
<P>
Not many years afterwards, the Chinese soldiers and residents
living in the Walled City fell into the clutches of the "evil from
the east" -- as they put it. During the Japanese occupation of
1941-45, the Japanese troops torn down the wall and used its
bricks and rocks to extend and reinforce the runway of nearby Kai
Tak Airport.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Walled City Tells of Hong Kong History (2) by Xu Xingtang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After the Japanese surrender, the old-day disorder was resumed
in the city.
</P>
<P>
The Sino-British Joint Declaration signed in 1984 laid down the
basis for giving the city a bright face-lift and improving the
living environment inside. In early 1987, China and the British
Hong Kong government reached an agreement to clear the area and
build a park on the site.
</P>
<P>
Now the place has become one of Hong Kong's busies tourist
attractions in the name of Kowloon Walled City Park. Since its
official opening in October 1995, it has received approximately
two million visitors.
</P>
<P>
"On weekends and public holidays we receive a daily average of
more than 5,000 visitors at weekends or on public holidays," said
Luk Pui-fong, manager of the park.
</P>
<P>
She said students from many schools are organized to visit the
park and learn the history of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Among the many local and overseas visitors, there are a group
of very special elderly people who come to the park every morning
-- the former dwellers of the city, who have moved to nearby
residential areas since the place was turned into the beautiful
park.
</P>
<P>
One of them, 65-year-old Wong Chit-fat, said: "I had lived here
since my birth in the walled city, and everything here will endure
in my mind, " he said, sitting in the wooden corridor of the park.
</P>
<P>
"As Hong Kong is soon to return to the motherland, it's a good
thing to build a so beautiful park here," he said.
</P>
<P>
Entering the South Gate of the park, a rockery of Taihu Lake
stone is in sight, on which there are two large Chinese characters
reading "Gui Bi", which means "returned jasper".
</P>
<P>
"It indicates Hong Kong's return to China," said Luk Pui-fong.
</P>
<P>
As one of the major sites for holding various activities in
celebration of Hong Kong's turn to the motherland. In the days
around July 1, quite a number of celebration programs will take
place in the park, the park manager said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
