<HEADLINE> Land Freeze Seen as Aiding Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Development of land for
non-farming purposes will be frozen this year to help revive
Shanghai's real estate market, today's China Daily cited
vice-mayor of the city Xia Keqiang as saying.
</P>
<P>
The vice-mayor said the city is mapping out a land-use plan for
1997 that will be submitted to the State Council for approval.
</P>
<P>
"At the same time," Xia said, "The city will take measures to
invigorate its real estate market.
</P>
<P>
"Land authorities are not entitled to accept the applications."
After booming for several years, the real estate market has
stagnated and is now saddled with empty housing units and idle
land.
</P>
<P>
Between 1991 and 1996, Shanghai authorized 84,337 hectares of
land for development. But 6,667 hectares remain undeveloped, a
significant loss to farm production.
</P>
<P>
Xia asked for fast resolution of such inefficient use of
land. "Nobody is allowed to use new land for real estate projects
this year," Xia told a real estate conference.
</P>
<P>
Key municipal woks and residential housing projects cannot
proceed without approval from the municipal government, the
vice-mayor stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
