<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Tightens Control Over Pollution From Cement Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, June 24 (Xinhua) -- China's cement manufacturers will
have to comply with the dust discharge standards set by the state
in the coming three years, said an official with the State Bureau
of Environmental Protection.
</P>
<P>
Those that fail to live up to the requirements within the
prescribed time limit will be shut down down, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The dust pollution in cement production has come under
state-level major control projects for the 1996-2000 period.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that more than six million tons of
dust are discharged in China every year and about 60 percent of
them are discharged by cement plants which number over 8,000.
</P>
<P>
The dust discharged by medium-sized and small cement plants
which account for 60 percent of the total has gone far beyond the
standards set by the state due mainly to their backward production
methods, the official said.
</P>
<P>
It was revealed that the State Economic and Trade Commission
has listed the backward indigenous cement production technology
in the backward technologies list for compulsory elimination. The
list is to be published soon.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the State Bureau of Environmental Protection and the
State Bureau of Building Materials will produce a series of
corresponding measures to standardize pollution control for the
cement industry.  
</P>
</TEXT>
