<HEADLINE> Indonesia Loses One Million Hectares of Farmland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia has lost almost one
million hectares of its farmland over the past five years, a
professor of agriculture said.
</P>
<P>
Bunasor Sanim, vice rector for finance and administration at
Bogor Agriculture Institute, told a seminar Monday that the
farmland had been converted to other uses such as industry,
infrastructure, human settlement and other urban development,
reports reaching here today said.
</P>
<P>
"About 50 to 60 percent of the converted farmland is in Java,"
he said after the opening of the seminar on sustainable
agriculture development in the year 2020.
</P>
<P>
This caused great productivity losses in the farming sector
because the soil in Java was highly fertile, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ministry of Agriculture, the agricultural
sector contributed only about 16.8 percent of the gross domestic
product (GDP) in 1994, but it employed 37.9 million or 46.1
percent of the workforce in the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
