<HEADLINE> GDP to Rise in Costa Rica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rican Central Bank
President Rodrigo Bolanos said today that the gross domestic
product (GDP) in the country will grow by 2.5 percent this year
while inflation will be below 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
This situation could bring about lower interest rates that
would contribute to reactivating of the economy, Bolanos said.
</P>
<P>
The monthly index of economic activity rose from 0.9 percent to
1.3 in the past six months, while exports rose five percent and
imports 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
An increase in the sale of cement during the past few months
seemed to indicate the reactivation of an important sector of the
economy, but the construction sector remained stagnant, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
Bolanos also highlighted the announcement of more than 300
million U.S. dollars worth of investment by the microchip
manufacturer, Intel, and the sale of 200 million dollars of
government bonds.
</P>
<P>
The trade deficit doubled, from 143 million dollars for the
first five months of 1996 to 309 million dollars in the same
period this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
