<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Surplus Workers Need New Concepts in Re-employment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- One third of the workers in
China's State-owned enterprises has been rendered redundant in the
course of reform and that has become a major challenge in
transforming the nation's unprofitable old industries, today's
"China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, with the establishment of a market economy and
the deepening of reforms in State enterprises, many unnecessary
positions were eliminated.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based English newspaper says that about 30 percent
of China's labour force works in the service industry. The ratio
is too low, even lower than that of some other developing
countries. Experts suggest China needs to create wider variety of
jobs for the redundancies.
</P>
<P>
In the past, State enterprises used to be the main channel for
taking in labor. But, with the deepening of reforms, the booming
private sector has provided an alternative.
</P>
<P>
The government is encouraging the development of private and
collective businesses to take in more surplus labor. But some people
continue to seek jobs in State enterprises, which are regarded as
more secure than those in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
In line with the situation, the government is trying to
complete its social security system to guarantee the basic needs
of the unemployed, and at the same time, encourage people to give
up their wait-and-see attitude and become more self-supporting.
</P>
<P>
With the fast pace of modernization, the service trade has
absorbed some of the labor, and the labour-intensive service
trade is a good alternative.
</P>
<P>
In the long run, an adequate market mechanism should be
cultivated in resettling the surplus labour, the paper says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
