<HEADLINE> Panama's Economy Reports 3.6 Percent Quarterly Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Panama's economy showed clear
signs of recovery with a 3.6 percent growth in the first quarter
of this year, Economic Planning Minister Guillermo Chapman said.
</P>
<P>
The quarterly growth relative to the same period of 1996 should
be attributed to a strong expansion in the country's construction,
electricity and port activities, Chapman told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
However, the minister acknowledged, restaurants, personal
services, commerce, international bank transactions and banana
production experienced a contraction during the three-month period.
</P>
<P>
The Panamanian economy benefited from favorable international
conditions such as low interest and inflation rates, he said.
</P>
<P>
The abundance of financial funds and the strong economic growth
in the United States since the end of 1996 have also played a part
in the Central American nation's economic recovery, Chapman noted.
</P>
<P>
Exports by Panama recorded a robust 3.3 percent rise during the
first quarter of 1997 compared with the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The chief economic planner forecast that Panama is likely to
register a 3.6 percent growth rate this year if the momentum
continues. Last year, the country's economy grew by 2.5 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
