<HEADLINE> Central China Starts Building Hydro-electric Power Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Work on the new Gaobazhou Hydropower
Station on the Qingjiang River that flows through an impoverished
part of central Hubei Province started recently.
</P>
<P>
It will have three generating units of 84,000 kw each and will
cost three billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
As an example of the policy of "first building power stations
and then getting management rights, developing river valleys, and
expanding hydro-electric power development in more areas," it is
expected to provide experience for hydro-electric power
development in the Three Gorges Dam on the middle reaches of the
Yangtze River and for stations on other rivers.
</P>
<P>
In the 1950s, experts put forward a plan for three separate
power stations on the river, which would have a combined
generating capacity of 3.05 million kw and could generate 8.5
billion kw/hours of electricity a year.
</P>
<P>
The first station, the Geheyan on the middle reaches of the
Qingjiang River, was completed in 1994 one year ahead of schedule
at a cost of five billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
It has a capacity of 1.2 million kw and has generated 9.5
billion kw/hours of electricity so far.
</P>
<P>
The Shuibuya Station's location on the upper reaches has been
decided on, and feasibility studies are being done.
</P>
<P>
When all three stations are finished they will play an
important role in balancing power with the Three Gorges Dam.
</P>
</TEXT>
