<HEADLINE> British Airways to Open New Routes to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 24 (Xinhua) -- British Airways plans to open
four new air routes between Britain and Chinese cities before
2000, a senior manager of the company announced in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The flights will link London with metropolitan Shanghai,
as well as south China's cities of Guangzhou, Zhuhai and Shenzhen,
said Charles Phelps-Penry, head of British Airway's office in
China.
</P>
<P>
At present, the airline runs three flights bound for Beijing
every week. It will open the fourth in March next year, and
eventually increase the frequency to seven flights a week, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The manager quoted an internaional association of airlines as
saying that the in- and out-bound passenger flow in China
will increas at an annual rate of 15 to 20 percent in the next four
to five years, much higher than the world average of 9.4
percent. He said if his company did not seize the opportunity, it
would loss China market in the cut-throat international
competition.
</P>
<P>
To cater to the Chinese passengers, British Airways plans to
recruit air stewards from China, serve Chinese-style food and
provide Chinese newspapers and magazines on board, he said.
</P>
