<HEADLINE> Shenzhen-bound Visa Process Simplified </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- There's no need to fill in the
entry-exit card, no need to pay visa fees, and even no need to
enter and exit from the same port for foreign visitors at Shenzhen
customes, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
This convenience is enjoyed every day by more than 330
foreigners, on average, as they enter Shenzhen Special Economic
Zone (SEZ) in south China from Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"We are greatly encouraged by the success the service has made
in attracting foreign tourists," the national English newspaper
quoted Jiang Xing, an official with Shenzhen Public Security
Bureau in South China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
After the handover of the bordering Hong Kong, she said, this
SEZ will improve the service by offering more favorable policies.
</P>
<P>
One that was just approved will grant separate visa for
foreigners who have special needs to leave Shenzhen for other
cities in China.
</P>
<P>
"Undoubtedly, the city can shorten its distance with the
outside world through these favors," Fang was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Starting in December 1994, the convenient entry-exit service
was co-organized by government departments in public security,
frontier inspection, tourism, foreign affairs and customs.
</P>
<P>
The special visa is valid for 72 hours. All foreign tourists
visiting Hong Kong can benefit from it except foreign
correspondents, senior foreign government officials and citizens
from countries that have not established diplomatic relations with
China.
</P>
<P>
But they have to enter Shenzhen from Hong Kong after having
organized into groups.
</P>
<P>
Besides exemption from filling in entry or exit cards, and
paying visa fees, foreigners holding this visa can enter and leave
freely from any of the five ports in Shenzhen - Luohu, Huanggang,
Shekou, Shatoujiao and Wenjindu.
</P>
<P>
So far, this visa had helped more than 17,000 foreign groups,
totaling 248,000 tourists, into Shenzhen by the end of last month.
</P>
<P>
During the first five months this year, more than 50,000
foreigners visited Shenzhen in 3,600 groups, accounting for
one-third of the total entry amount, according to China Daily. 
</P>
</TEXT>
