<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Boost Paddy Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar will launch special
projects for boosting paddy output, The New Light of Myanmar
newspaper said today.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar Minister for Agriculture and Irrigation Myint Aung told
a meeting Monday that the projects will cover water availability,
agricultural education and financial assistance.
</P>
<P>
Dams in the country's states and divisions will be fully
utilized for irrigation, he said.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that Myanmar's total paddy output in the 1996-97
fiscal year ending March failed to reach the planned target of 20
million tons.
</P>
<P>
He said plans had been drawn up to extend cultivation of beans,
cotton, sugarcane, coffee, rubber, jute and maize.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's paddy output in the 1995-96 fiscal year was recorded
at 19 million tons with 353,100 tons exported.
</P>
<P>
For the whole year of 1996, the rice export was 271,900 tons as
compared with 637,100 tons the previous year, according to
official figures.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's gross domestic product (GDP) grew by 5.8 percent in
1996-97. Agricultural production went up by 3.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has set a target of 6.4 percent growth for 1997-98 with
the agricultural sector to grow by 6.3 per cent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
