<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Briefs From Mercosur </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The following are news briefs
from the Southern Common Market (Mercosur) in the past few days:
</P>
<P>
ASUNCION -- During the 12th Mercosur summit, the four
presidents from the bloc member countries agreed to intensify
integration and accept Chile and Bolivia to the organization's
negotiations vis-a-vis the Free Trade Area of the Americas.
</P>
<P>
At that summit held here on June 18-19, the presidents of
Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay, the Mercosur partners,
urged that the mechanisms required for the compliance of the
objective be established within six months.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The Brazilian government decided to extend the
exemption granted to its Mercosur partners on its import
restrictions for another three months.
</P>
<P>
The exemptions, which were to expire July 31, will continue
until October 31.
</P>
<P>
Treasury Minister Pedro Malan said that during the period of
credit restrictions, there was a very significant increase in
Brazilian imports from Chile and Bolivia because the restrictions
reduced the financial gains that were were being obtained by
importers through the use of commercial loans.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentine Economy Minister Roque Fernandez
denied that there was a subsidy war between his country and Brazil
in the face of Brazil's refusal to eliminate import restrictions.
</P>
<P>
The minister denied that Argentina will modify its current
position on domestic industrial promotion.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- On June 19, the Chamber of Industries in Uruguay
(CIU) rejected again the measures implemented by Brazil on April 1
to restrict imports.
</P>
<P>
The CIU said the Brazilian resolution is, in reality, a
protectionistic measure and it provokes uncertainty and loss of
credibility in the Mercosur integration process.
</P>
<P>
ASUNCION -- The Mercosur parliamentary committee agreed to set
up a court to resolve the disputes among its members.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting which ended here on June 20, the committee also
decided to draft a Mercosur letter that will suggest the
homogenizing of labor protection laws. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
