<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Maternal Mortality Down in Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Maternal mortality in Mexico
was down 27.7 percent between 1994-96, said a report available
today from the Mexican Social Security Institute.
</P>
<P>
The death rate dropped from 57.6 deaths for every 100,000 live
births in 1994 to 29.9 per 100,000 in 1996, said the Reproductive
Health Program of the institute, known as IMSS in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the lower mortality rate among the
country's pregnant women to their increased participation in
reproductive health programs developed by various institutions.
</P>
<P>
These programs offer comprehensive attention to women at
child-bearing ages and their infants by covering areas such as
prenatal and infant health, family planning and adolescent care.
</P>
<P>
The IMSS assisted in 842,000 deliveries or obstetric events in
1994, but the figure was down to 663,000 in 1996 thanks to better
access to higher quality prenatal, maternal and infant care.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Six Teams Qualify for Volleyball World League Finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Six teams have qualified for the
men's volleyball World League finals in Moscow as games in three
pools concluded on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 100,000 spectators saw Cuba, Brazil, Italy, Bulgaria,
Netherlands and Russia qualify for Moscow finals slated from June
30th to July 5th.
</P>
<P>
In Pool A, Brazil had a difficult second match against Japan
with young Japanese players finding themselves in good fighting
spirit and even taking one set. In Rosario, Argentina gave a hard
time to Bulgaria, even leading 2-1 in the second match.
</P>
<P>
In a crowded stadium in Belgrade in Pool B, Yugoslavia was
leading Italy in the first two sets of the first match before the
injury of its captain Dejan Brdjovic allowed Bebetto's players to
rally and win the first match.
</P>
<P>
The second match went to the tie-break and Yugoslavia finally
took over 15-12. They had preserved a small chance to qualify for
Moscow and had to wait for the result of Argentina against
Bulgaria to face the final and bitter decision to be excluded from
the final six.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, a reborned Chinese team imposed two straight
defeats to a disheartened Spanish team.
</P>
<P>
In Pool C, Russia at home, playing with a complete roster, did
not have much problem to dispose off a South Korean team,
physically weakened and incapable to display its usual fighting
spirit.
</P>
<P>
The real suspense was in Cuba. In front of 20,000 spectators,
the young Cubans imposed their superior attack and block against a
Dutch team fighting on every point.
</P>
<P>
The second match was a thriller, each team taking the lead by
turn, before the Dutchmen took over in the tie-break to win the
match and their tickets for the finals in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
On July 5, top two teams in the six-member round-robin
tournament will vie for the 1997 World League Champion title and a
prize money of 1,000,000 US dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
