<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong to Play Greater Role: Senior Government Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong will have closer
economic relations with China's interior areas after its return to
the motherland on July 1, according to a senior government
official.
</P>
<P>
After Hong Kong's return, the advantages of Hong Kong and the
interior areas will be combined better and that will produce
greater economic returns, said Rafael Hui Si-yan, secretary for
Financial Service of the future Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region government.
</P>
<P>
"After its return to the motherland, Hong Kong will be able to
continue to bring its special advantages into full play, help
implement the country's reform and open-up policy, and contribute
to the economic construction of the inland areas," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hui, 49, who joined the public service after graduation from
Hong Kong University in 1970, became the first Chinese secretary
for Financial Service in the British Hong Kong government in
September 1995.
</P>
<P>
In Hong Kong, an economic metropolis, civil servants in charge
of making economic policy decisions must have a good knowledge of
the city's economic operation, and understand what manufacturers
and business people are thinking about, he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the main function of the Financial Service Branch
is to formulate government financial and monetary policies, and
set targets for the financial policy, so that Hong Kong will
maintain a "fair, efficient and vibrant" market operational and
regulatory mechanism that meet international standards.
</P>
<P>
"This will help to ensure the competitiveness of Hong Kong in
the Asia-Pacific region and in the world as a whole, and to retain
Hong Kong's status as an international financial center," he said.
</P>
<P>
For Hong Kong industrialists and business people, it is
important to learn about the latest economic information, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Census and Statistics Department under the
charge of the Financial Services Branch is in charge of providing
economic statistics for investors and research institutes both at
home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
By collecting various kinds of economic data, staff of the
department regularly release statistics, which have become an
indispensable component of Hong Kong's economic life, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released by the department are in line with the
principle of factual accuracy, and are not subject to the
influence of other factors.
</P>
<P>
"The department releases both good news and bad news," he said.
</P>
<P>
Both local companies and overseas investors rely on these
statistics to make their commercial decisions, he said, noting:
"If the figures are not accurate, market operation will be
adversely affected."
</P>
<P>
Factors that have contributed to Hong Kong's economic success
have been reflected in the Basic Law, he said.
</P>
<P>
"So long as we failthfully implement the Basic Law, we shall be
able to make sure that Hong Kong will continue to maintain its
status as an international financial center," Hui said.
</P>
<P>
To enhance its competitiveness in the world market, Hong Kong
should always maintain its export-oriented economic model, the
regulation of the market operation to be fair and transparent, and
a free flow of information, as well as to ensure the quality of
professionals in all sectors, he said..
</P>
<P>
On economic prospects, he said as a special administrative
region of the People's Republic of China, Hong Kong would be in a
"very favorable" position. For example, by utilizing its
experience in financial service and its advantageous position, it
can raise funds for national construction and enterprises in the
inland areas.
</P>
<P>
The Asia-Pacific region is the region that has scored the
fastest economic growth in the world, and China is the country
that has achieved the most rapid economic growth in the
Asia-Pacific Region, he said.
</P>
<P>
As a major bridge linking China with the rest of the world,
Hong Kong will certainly be able to play an even greater role in
the future, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
