<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Faces One Million Jobs Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The labor market in Mexico has
a deficit of 1.052 million jobs at present, according to figures
provided by the National Statistics, Geography and Computer
Database Institute (INEGI).
</P>
<P>
Only 430,000 new jobs in the formal sectors were created during
the first five months of this year, not enough to meet the demand
for jobs which amounted to 1.482 million.
</P>
<P>
For its part the informal economic sector has served as a
cushion for labor market adjustments, by absorbing a substantial
portion of the excess labor supply.
</P>
<P>
Experts said underemployment prevailed as a structural problem
of the economy since those who worked less than 15 hours a week
accounted for 5 percent of the total labor market, the highest
rate in the last 14 months.
</P>
<P>
Underemployment affected close to 1.826 million Mexicans who
have been rejected because of downsizing and who are looking for
work within an environment of latent unemployment, the INEGI
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
