<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Planned Merger of State Banks a Positive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank (WB) views the
planned merger of some state-owned banks by the Indonesian
government as a positive step towards attaining greater
efficiency, a spokesman for the bank said here.
</P>
<P>
"We are very pleased to hear the news," World Bank
representative in Indonesia Dannis De Tray said in a discussion on
"Indonesia sustaining high growth with equity" here on Monday,
sources at the meeting said today.
</P>
<P>
The plans to merge the state banks represented an admission by
the government of the need to rethink the state banking system as
a whole, he said.
</P>
<P>
On June 21, President Soeharto approved plans to merge the
country's seven state-owned banks to improve their performance and
competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
The government's plan to merge the state banks concurred with a
World Bank recommendation included in the bank's report to be
presented at a meeting of the Consultative Group for Indonesia
(CGI) scheduled for July 19, De Tray said.
</P>
<P>
De Tray also said Indonesia's economic growth would continue to
be strong over the next year and is expected to be about 7.75
percent this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
