<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, US to Launch Chemical Joint-Venture Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- China is planning another massive
petrochemical plant as it races to become self-sufficient in
oil-derived commodities essential for domestic economic growth,
today's "China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
US-based Dow Chemical Co and China Petrochemical Co (Sinopec)
signed a letter of intent Monday to establish a world-class
integrated petrochemical joint venture in Tianjin. The complex has
a projected production capacity of 600,000 tons of ethylene, and
facilities to make related products such as polyethylene and resin.
</P>
<P>
Each partner is expected to hold 50 percent of the equity of
the three billion US dollars project. The venture, one of China's
six major ethylene projects planned for the 1996-2000 period, will
enhance the position of the petrochemical industry as the nation's
economic pillar. All six projects will each be capable of
producing 600,000 tons or more of ethylene yearly.
</P>
<P>
China is poised to lift the total production capacity of
ethylene to five million tons by 2000, a sharp boost from three
million tons in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Last year alone, China imported 6.5 million tons of polyester,
1.5 million tons of chemical fiber and 400,000 tons of synthetic
fiber. The paper says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
