<HEADLINE> Automobile Production Up in Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Brazil is expected to roll
out two million vehicles this year, a 100 percent increase over
that of five years ago, said an industry group.
</P>
<P>
The largest Latin American nation's auto production surpassed
the one million unit mark for the first time in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The rapid rise, said the National Association of Automobile
Manufacturers in a report published today, is the result of
government policies encouraging the growth of the auto industry.
</P>
<P>
Last year the government adopted policies to encourage
automakers to build plants in poor areas of northeastern, northern
and central western Brazil and help boost local economies there.
</P>
<P>
Japanese, French and U.S. investors said they would invest an
equivalent of 2.8 billion U.S. dollars in those areas over the
next five years, said the association. 
</P>
</TEXT>
