<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ban on Development of Small Thermal Power Stations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Provincial authorities of
central China's Henan have banned construction of thermal power
stations with generating capacities below 100,000 kw.
</P>
<P>
The authorities will encourage different localities to finance
large-capacity power plants, so as to meet the demand for transfer
of economic growth mode in the power industry and to suit the
demand of environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Over past years, Henan has witnessed fast expansion in its
power industry. Small thermal power stations in some areas have
been tangled in a fight for a bigger share of the power market.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, the province had owned moderate and
low pressure generating units with a combined capacity of 3.1
million kw, accounting for 28 percent of the province's total
generating capacity.
</P>
<P>
Construction of small thermal power stations across the
province with an aggregate generating capacity of 1.5 million kw,
is still being carried out swiftly, while more localities have
proposed that new small thermal stations with three million kw be
constructed.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government said in its decree that they would
tighten macro control over small thermal power stations in
different localities and be strict with the approving procedures
for these projects, stipulating that small thermal power stations
without permit will get no loans, nor land allocation.
</P>
<P>
People held responsible for getting small thermal power
stations approved and constructed without proper authorization
from the day when the decree is made known to the public, which
have also caused environmental pollution or economic losses to the
state or the collective, will be severely dealt with. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
