<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Seeds Advance at Wimbledon Tennis Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WIMBLEDON, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The 1997 Wimbledon Tennis
Championships kicked off at the All England Law Tennis Club in
south London on Monday with major seeds battling into the second
round.
</P>
<P>
Defending champion Richard Krajicek of the Netherlands met with
fierce resistance from German Marcello Craca at the first set, but
the towering Dutch player gradually consolidated his position on
the grassland, gave his opponent no further chance by winning 7-6,
6-2, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
"These are the kind of matches that you just have to win and
you don't look for beauty," said Krajicek, "I felt pretty
pressured as defending champion and I felt a little bit nervous
but it was a great feeling to get through this match."
</P>
<P>
Second seed Goran Ivanisevic of Croatia, who is regarded as one
of the most powerful servers, enjoyed a smooth sailing by
defeating Romanian Dinu Pescariu, ranked 106th in the world, 6-1,
6-3, 6-3 in just 64 minutes.
</P>
<P>
British top player Tim Henman, who received a deafening cheers
from the home crowds, put up a wonderful show by ousting Daniel
Nestor of Canada 7-6 (13-11), 6-1, 6-4 in his opening match.
</P>
<P>
In the women's events, fourth seed Iva Majoli, who won the
French Open by defeating world number one Martina Hingus, lost her
first set 2-6 to Argentina's Mariana Diaz Oliva.
</P>
<P>
But the 19-year-old Croatian fought back bravely by snatching
the following two sets 6-0, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
A jubilant Majoli said: "When I won this match I was almost as
happy as when I won the French Open. It was like a release."
</P>
<P>
The women's fifth seed American Lindsay Davenport and 12th seed
Irina Spirlea of Romania also sailed into the second round by
beating American Tami Jones 5-7, 6-2, 6-2 and Slovakian Henrieta
Nagyova 6-1, 6-0 respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
