<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Project Promotes Clean Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- A Sino-Canadian project on cleaner
production has been inaugurated to promote environmentally
sustainable industrial development in China, today's "China Daily"
reports.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based English newspaper quotes a State Economic and
Trade Commission (SETC) official as saying that a two-day workshop
was recently held in east China's Anhui province on cleaner
production audits as an inauguration for this project.
</P>
<P>
Cleaner production, which tries to remove health hazards and
environmental damage, has been listed among the first batch of
priority programmes in China's Agenda 21, a national blueprint for
sustainable growth.
</P>
<P>
The Sino-Canadian project is led by the SETC on the Chinese
side. It is organized and implemented jointly by the commission
and Nepa, with the Canadian International Development Agency as
its sponsor.
</P>
<P>
Budgeted at over 10 million Canadian dollars, and with the same
value of Chinese input, the project will work out policies and
regulations to put cleaner production into practice.
</P>
<P>
Another task is to help the demonstration enterprises find
solutions for cleaner production on the basis of audit results,
and to compile guidelines of cleaner production for the major
polluting industries of the Huaihe River Valley. The paper
says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
