<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Household Appliances Growth Gains Momentum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- China is now the third largest
market for household electrical appliances with sales of the
products accounting for seven percent of the world's total in 1996,
according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
China's sales of household electrical appliances were 110
billion yuan (13 billion US dollars) in 1996, with world total
sales amounting to 200 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Only the United States and Japan have larger market shares,
according to the industry's annual working conference, which
opened Monday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The household electrical appliance industry maintained a 32
percent growth during 1986-95, faster than in any other country.
</P>
<P>
Production of major products, such as refrigerators, washing
machines, electric irons, fans and cookers, is the largest in the
world. Production of other products including air conditioners is
also among the largest, the conference reported.
</P>
<P>
Exports of household electrical appliances have increased about
20 percent annually in the past several years, with total exports
topping 2.75 billion US dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
China's appliance products have been sent to more than 100
countries and regions. Annual exports of 12 manufacturers exceed
10 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Although challenged by severe competition from multinational
companies, China's household electrical appliance industry has
established a firm position in the national market.
</P>
<P>
A survey of appliance sales in 100 large department stores in
35 cities showed all the top 10 brands are domestic.
</P>
<P>
Domestic-made refrigerators share 93 percent of the market,
freezers 89 percent, washing machines 83 percent and air
conditioners 57 percent.
</P>
<P>
All these achievements are significant since China's household
electrical appliance industry has developed from almost nothing,
said Yang Zhihai, vice-chairman of China National Council of
Light Industry.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1980s, less than five percent of urban families owned
a refrigerator, but in 1996 about 70 percent of urban families had
a refrigerator. Nearly 12 percent of urban families had air
conditioners in 1996, while very few families in the early 1980s
could afford the luxury product.
</P>
<P>
Through competition among themselves as well as against strong
foreign companies, some Chinese appliance enterprises have built
up famous brand names and established an economy of scale.
</P>
<P>
Basically a processing industry, the appliance industry has to
be an economy of scale to be profitable.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
