<HEADLINE> Three Former US Presidents Support MFN for China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Former presidents George Bush,
Gerald Ford and Jimmy Carter today expressed their support for the
extension of the MFN trade status for China in their separate
letters to the incumbent President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Bush said in his letter, released by the White House,
"Withholding MFN is not a sensible approach to resolving our
differences (between the two countries). Quite on the contrary, I
am convinced that withholding MFN, of even conditioning its
application to China, would be severely counterproductive."
</P>
<P>
The three former presidents' letters followed those that fed
the same support for the renewal of the MFN status for China.
</P>
<P>
A letter from former secretaries of state said, "MFN revocation
would effectively cut off trade between our two countries and
thereby deal a devastating blow to our overall relationship. It
would undermine the progress we have made working with China on
critical issues, from stability on the Korean Peninsula to
stemming the flow of illegal aliens and narcotics."
</P>
<P>
Ten former defense secretaries made the same expression.
</P>
<P>
They said the most promising way to solve differences between
the two countries is "for the United States to continue to build a
relationship of mutual engagement with China." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
