<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Developed Countries Urged to Honor Commitments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 23 (Xinhua) -- President of Tanzania
Benjamin W. Mkapa today urged the developed countries to honor
their commitments on official development aid (ODA) and addressing
environmental degradation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on behalf of the "Group of 77" and China at the Earth
Summit+5, he said that it had been agreed at Rio to reach the UN
target of developed countries contributing 0.7 percent of their
gross national product to ODA. That contribution had declined
since Rio from 0.34 percent in 1992 to 0.25 percent now.
</P>
<P>
"Each decline in ODA erodes the capacity of developing
countries to implement Rio agreements and action plan," he said.
</P>
<P>
The global Environment Facility capital also needed to be
increased substantially to enable it to provide adequate finance for
programs that were within its mandate, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Africa's external debt was unsustainable. "While
recent initiatives for debt relief are welcome, when criteria for
eligibility are too stringent or when promised relief is to be
realized in the too distant future, `the medicine may arrive when
the patient is beyond help.'"
</P>
<P>
He also urged the developed countries to transfer technologies
to developing countries on a predictable and sustainable basis.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the environmental degradation caused by unsustainable
patterns of consumption and production, particularly in developed
countries, should be addressed, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The current special session should mark the beginning of a
global partnership for sustainable development through increased
ODA and direct investment, for financing capacity building, and
for preferential and unrestricted access to the market of
developed countries, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
