<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Song Jian Urges Closing of Gap Between Words, Deeds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Chinese State Councillor
Song Jian said today that to close the gap between words and deeds
should be the key to promoting international
environment-and-development cooperation in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Song made the remarks in his address to the U.N. Special
Session on Environment. The meeting comes five years after a
summit in Rio de Janeiro where 10,000 diplomats and
environmentalists outlined an ambitious blueprint to safeguard the
planet, which is known as Agenda 21.
</P>
<P>
On the past five years' work, Song said that the international
community has made notable achievements in implementing the Rio
Declaration and Agenda 21.
</P>
<P>
"Of these the most outstanding are that the concept of
sustainable development has begun taking root in people's minds,
permeating among all sectors of economic and social life and
becoming the guiding principle of countries in formulating their
development strategy," he said.
</P>
<P>
But, he said, "there is still quite a gap between what we have
done and what needs to be done to realize a global sustainable
development." Till now, most developed countries have not made
good their commitments. The percentage of their official
development aid in GNP has dropped to the lowest level in 25
years. Some developed countries are pursuing new trade
protectionism under the pretext of environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that to fully implement the concept of protecting
the environment in the course of development and to close the gap
between words and deeds should be the theme of the special session
of this Assembly and the key to promoting international
environment-and-development cooperation in the 21st century," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Our objective is to achieve a global sustainable development
in the 21st century," Song said. "To strengthen cooperation is the
only way to fulfill this historical mission."
</P>
<P>
Song put forward three proposals on how to strengthen
international cooperation in the field of environment.
</P>
<P>
First, developed countries have the capability and unshirkable
historical responsibility to share with developing countries the
achievement of a new round of scientific and technological
revolution, he said.
</P>
<P>
Second, more favorable conditions should be created, according
to the principles enshrined in the Rio Declaration and Agenda 21,
for developing countries in their economic development and
environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
"The most important issue at present is to overcome trade
protectionism of various kinds and to establish an equitable,
rational and integrated multilateral trading system so as to
facilitate the positive interaction of trade and environment," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Third, strong measures should be taken to reverse the trend of
sharp decrease in development funding for developing countries.
</P>
<P>
"Adequate financial resources are a necessary condition to
improve the capability of developing countries in the
implementation of Agenda 21," he said.
</P>
<P>
Song also gave advice to the developing countries on how to
pursue sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
"The developing countries, while actively seeking international
support and assistance, should fully tap their own potentials," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"They cannot and should not follow the same old development
patterns of developed countries in `pollution first and treatment
later,' but rather take the road of sustainable development right
from the initial stage of development," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970624.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Song Jian on China's Implementation of Agenda 21 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Chinese State Councillor
Song Jian told the U.N. Special Session on Environment today that
China has achieved great progress in the field of sustainable
development since the 1992 Earth Summit.
</P>
<P>
"I am glad to report to this Assembly that while registering
rapid economic growth in recent years, China has basically avoided
drastic environmental degradation and even registered some partial
improvement in the nation's environment," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Special Session on Environment comes five years after
the Earth Summit in Rio de Janeiro where 10,000 diplomats and
environmentalists outlined an ambitious blueprint to safeguard the
planet, which is later known as Agenda 21.
</P>
<P>
In a six-page speech to the Special Session, Song Jian outlined
six areas where China has gained progress by promoting sustainable
development according to Agenda 21:
</P>
<P>
-- Since the early 1990s, China's GNP has been growing at an
average annual rate of more than 10 percent and the
poverty-stricken population has declined from 80 million to 58
million at present;
</P>
<P>
-- Rapid population growth has been brought under control and
the nation's natural population growth rate has dropped steadily;
</P>
<P>
-- Notable achievements have been made in comprehensively
utilizing resources by promoting their conservation and by relying
on scientific and technological progress;
</P>
<P>
-- Efforts have been made to promote clean production
processes. The increase in discharged pollutants has been
effectively curbed by the closing down of 62,000 seriously
polluting enterprises;
</P>
<P>
-- More attention has been given to forest cultivation and a
nation-wide voluntary afforestation drive. Man-made forests now
cover 34.25 million hectares. Forest coverage increased from 12.98
percent in 1992 to 13.92 percent in 1996;
</P>
<P>
-- Greater efforts have been devoted to preserving
bio-diversity. A network of nature reserves has basically taken
shape, covering 71.85 million hectares or 7.2 percent of China's
total territory. Most of the endangered species are being
affectively protected.
</P>
<P>
Song told the assembly that these achievements have been scored
by the Chinese people and government by mainly relying on their
own efforts, which proves the effectiveness of China's policy of
integrating environmental and economic development.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with Agenda 21, he said, China took the lead to
formulate "China's Agenda 21," -- the White Paper on China's
Population, Environment and Development in the 21st Century, which
sets forth the guiding principles of holistic planning and
coordinated development of economy, society, resources and
environment.
</P>
<P>
Noting the severe environmental challenges China is still
faced, Song expressed optimism towards the future of the country
in accomplishing the goals of basically providing adequate food
and clothing to the poverty-stricken population by the end of the
century, achieving zero population growth around the year of 2030
and doing a good job in environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
"As the biggest developing country in the world, China will
contribute significantly to global environmental protection and
economic development by running her own affairs well," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
