<HEADLINE> Former Defense Secretaries Back China MFN Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Ten former U.S. defense
secretaries today sent a letter to President Bill Clinton,
supporting his decision to extend China's MFN trade status for the
coming year.
</P>
<P>
They said, "American interests are best served by a secure,
stable and open China." Revoking the MFN status for China could be
interpreted as "adopting of a policy of confrontation by the
United States," they said.
</P>
<P>
They said differences between the two countries should not be
resolved simply by cutting the normal trade relations between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
The letter was signed by William Perry, Dick Cheney, Harold
Brown, Frank Carlucci, Clark Clifford, Robert McNamara, Melvin
Laird, Elliot Richardson, Donald Rumsfeld and James Schlesinger.
</P>
</TEXT>
