<HEADLINE> Annan Deplores "Atrocities" of UN Force in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 23 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan today deplored the alleged atrocities committed while on
duty in Somalia by the United Nations peacekeeping soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the alleged wrongdoings of Italian soldiers in
Somalia in 1994, Annan said in his statement, "I am appalled and
outraged by the actions which are unacceptable and countering to
everything peacekeeping stands for," said a statement released by
the spokesman's office.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, Annan said that United Nations peacekeeping
soldiers were and should be held to the highest standard of
service and conduct. Training of soldiers in their
responsibilities to citizens, refugees and others facing hardships
had been strengthened since 1993.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general stressed that every possible effort would
be made on the part of the United Nations to ensurer that such
incidents would not recur.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed his deep faith and pride in the valor,
commitment and service of thousands of peacekeeping soldiers from
more than 70 countries.
</P>
<P>
There were reports about the pictures showing cruel torturing of
Somalis by the Italian peacekeepers in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
