<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Public Teachers Allowed to Help Church Pupils </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The Supreme Court of the United
States today, overturning its 1985 church-state decision, ruled
that public school teachers can offer remedial help at religious
schools.
</P>
<P>
The 5-4 decision is expected to save millions of dollars a year
in administrative costs for a federal program to help children
from low-income families.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton said in a statement that the
court's ruling "will raise educational standards for children
across America."
</P>
<P>
A 1965 law known as Title I requires federally funded remedial
help for underachieving students from low-income families, no
matter what school they attend. But the Supreme Court ruled in
1985 the practice unconstitutionally broke down the wall between
church and state.
</P>
<P>
Since then, religious school children who qualify have been
getting the remedial help in public schools or other venues such
as in mobile vans parked just off parochial school property or by
computer.
</P>
<P>
Department of Education officials estimate the annual cost
nationwide to be 15 million U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
