<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Plunges 192 Points </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The Dow Jones industrial average
suffered its worst point drop since the crash of 1987 as rising
interest rates spurred a spree of profit-taking on Wall Street's
record-setting advance.
</P>
<P>
The Dow plunged 192.25 points to 7.604.26. It was the blue-chip
barometer's biggest point-drop since it lost 508 points on the
Black Monday crash of October 19, 1987 and slightly more than a
190.58-point drop in October 1989.
</P>
<P>
Both of those drops were far more significant in percentage
terms than today's 2.5 percent slide, however, because the Dow has
more than tripled in value over the past 10 years. Last week, the
Dow broke above 7,800 for the first time, closing at a record-high
7,796.51 Friday.
</P>
<P>
Decliners outnumbered advancers by more than a 2-to-1 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with its volume being decreased to
492.69 million shares, down from 653.11 million in the previous
session.
</P>
<P>
Other major indexes also slid sharply today.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 20.08 points to
878.62, and the NYSE composite index fell 9.35 to 458.49.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index fell 12.77 to 1,434.33, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index fell 2.85 to 620.42.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
