<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former FBI Agent Sentenced to 27 Years for Spying </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. District Court in
Alexandria, Va., today sentenced a former agent of the Federal
Bureau of Investigation (FBI) to 27 years in prison for spying for
Moscow during and after the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
Earl Pitts, 44, had been charged with selling U.S.
intelligences secrets to the Russians for more than 224,000 U.S.
dollars from 1987 to 1992.
</P>
<P>
The 13-year FBI veteran was arrested at the FBI training
academy in Quantico, Va. last December for passing vital national
security secrets to Russian intelligence agencies.
</P>
<P>
He was the second FBI agent sentenced for spying for foreign
nations. The other FBI agent ever caught spying was Richard W.
Miller, a Los Angeles agent who was arrested in 1984 and later
sentenced to 20 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, CIA agent Harold Nicholson was sentenced to
23 years for selling secrets to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
Pitts sought out a Soviet agent and offered his services while
stationed in Moscow in 1987 before moving to the FBI's New York
office, where he was assigned to hunt and recruit KGB officers.
From 1989 to 1992, he worked on top-secret records and personnel
security at FBI headquarters in Washington.
</P>
<P>
The FBI said Pitts turned over a secret computerized FBI list
of all Soviet officials in the United States with their known or
suspected posts in Soviet spy agencies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
